{"title_page": "Abdur Razzak (cricketer)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzak Rajib}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Abdur Razzak <br /> \u0986\u09ac\u09cd\u09a6\u09c1\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09cd\u099c\u09be\u0995\n|               image = Adbur Razzak bowling 2010.jpg\n|             country = Bangladesh\n|            fullname = Abdur Razzak\n|            nickname = Raj\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1982|6|15|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Khulna]], Bangladesh\n|                role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = [[Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n|       international = true\n|   internationalspan = 2004\u20132018\n|       testdebutdate = 16 April\n|       testdebutyear = 2006\n|    testdebutagainst = Australia\n|             testcap = 45\n|        lasttestdate = 8 February\n|        lasttestyear = 2018\n|     lasttestagainst = Sri Lanka\n|        odidebutdate = 16 July\n|        odidebutyear = 2004\n|     odidebutagainst = Hong Kong\n|              odicap = 1\n|         lastodidate = 25 August\n|         lastodiyear = 2014\n|      lastodiagainst = West Indies\n|            odishirt = 41\n|       T20Idebutdate = 28 November\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2006\n|    T20Idebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n|             T20Icap = 1\n|        lastT20Idate = 27 August\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2014\n|     lastT20Iagainst = West Indies\n|               club1 = [[Khulna Division cricket team|Khulna Division]]\n|               year1 = 2001\u2013present\n|               club2 = [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]]\n|               year2 = 2008\n|               club3 = [[Rangpur Riders]]\n|               year3 = 2013\u2013present\n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 13\n|               runs1 = 245\n|            bat avg1 = 17.50\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 43\n|         deliveries1 = 2,817\n|            wickets1 = 28\n|           bowl avg1 = 59.75\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 4/63\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 4/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches2 = 153\n|               runs2 = 779\n|            bat avg2 = 13.43\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/1\n|          top score2 = 53[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries2 = 7,965\n|            wickets2 = 207\n|           bowl avg2 = 29.29\n|            fivefor2 = 4\n|             tenfor2 = 0\n|       best bowling2 = 5/29\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 32/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n|            matches3 = 34\n|               runs3 = 41\n|            bat avg3 = 4.10\n|           100s/50s3 = 0/0\n|          top score3 = 9\n|         deliveries3 = 730\n|            wickets3 = 44\n|           bowl avg3 = 19.04\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 4/16\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 10/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches4 = 128\n|               runs4 = 2,725\n|            bat avg4 = 17.58\n|           100s/50s4 = 0/10\n|          top score4 = 97\n|         deliveries4 = 34,708\n|            wickets4 = 581\n|           bowl avg4 = 28.95\n|            fivefor4 = 38\n|             tenfor4 = 10\n|       best bowling4 = 9/84\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 50/\u2013\n|                date = 4 May\n|                year = 2019\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/player/56283.html CricInfo\n}}\n'''Abdur Razzak''' ({{lang-bn|\u0986\u09ac\u09cd\u09a6\u09c1\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09cd\u099c\u09be\u0995}}; born 15 June 1982) is a Bangladeshi [[cricket]]er, who currently plays [[Test cricket]] and retired from [[Limited overs cricket|limited overs format]] of the game. Razzak is the first Bangladeshi to take 200 wickets in [[One Day International|ODIs]]. He is also the first left arm spinner and 2nd spinner after [[Saqlain Mushtaq]] took a [[Hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]].\n\nHe made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut at Bangladeshi domestic level for Khulna Division in the 2001/02 season. Best known for being a tall [[left-arm orthodox spin]] bowler, he helped guide his division to the National Cricket Title in his maiden season. From there he was selected for Bangladesh A (training team for the full national squad) performing well against [[Zimbabwean cricket team|Zimbabwe A]], including figures of 7 for 17 in one game in [[Dhaka]].\n\nThough he has played just nine Tests, he has been more successful in [[One Day International]]s (ODIs) and was Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in the format in 2013, when he reached the 200 wickets milestone. <ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=2;id=25;type=team |title=Records / Bangladesh / One-Day Internationals / Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2011-10-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330230720/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=2%3Bid%3D25%3Btype%3Dteam |archivedate=30 March 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, he became the first Bangladesh player to take 500 wickets in first-class cricket.<ref name=first>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22131211/abdur-razzak-tushar-imran-climb-first-class-summits |title=Abdur Razzak and Tushar Imran climb first-class summits |author=Isam, Mohammad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 January 2018|date=17 January 2018 }}</ref> After four years, he made comeback to the Test squad on 8 February 2018 [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2017\u201318|against Sri Lanka]], taking 4-63 opening the bowling, but Bangladesh lost by 215 runs.<ref name=razzaqcomeback>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18527/report/1130745/bangladesh-vs-sri-lanka-2nd-test-sri-lanka-tour-of-bangladesh-2018 |title=Sri Lanka bat; Abdur Razzak returns after four years |author=Fernando, Andrew Fidel |publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> In November 2019, he took his 600th first-class wicket, becoming the first Bangladeshi bowler to reach the milestone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27987347/abdur-razzak-becomes-first-bangladeshi-bowler-bag-600-first-class-wickets |title=Abdur Razzak becomes first Bangladeshi bowler to bag 600 first-class wickets |author=Isam, Mohammad |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=2 November 2019 |accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n===Indian Premier League===\nRazzak was the only Bangladeshi to play in the [[2008 Indian Premier League]] making him the first Bangladeshi to play the league. He was bought for $50,000 by the [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]] and played in only one match. Despite not playing often for the team, Razzak believed that the experience he gained from the tournament was important. He stated that [[Anil Kumble]] \"was very helpful when I asked him about bowling in Test matches. He told me that given my bowling approach, it is very important to use variations within my line and length. Actually, captains would want a breakthrough from me so without using variations, wickets are hard to come by. Coach Venkatesh Prasad was also a great help\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/353083.html |title=Experience was more important than money&nbsp;\u2013 Razzak |date=31 May 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh domestic career===\nRazzak responded by taking his best bowling figures in first-class cricket (8/123). His match haul of 15/193 against [[Barisal Division cricket team|Barisal Division]] were the best in the history of the [[National Cricket League of Bangladesh|National Cricket League]], breaking the record set three years previously by [[Elias Sunny]], the bowler who had replaced Razzak in the Test team.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-domestic-2011/content/story/538053.html |title=Abdur Razzak's record-haul leads Khulna to win |first=Mohammad |last=Islam |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/537129.html |title=Ashraful must perform to play&nbsp;\u2013 Law |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-19}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, he was the leading wicket-taker in the [[2017\u201318 Bangladesh Cricket League]], with 43 dismissals in six matches, a record for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=12213;type=tournament |title=Bangladesh Cricket League 2017/18: Most Wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> He was also the leading wicket-taker in the [[2018\u201319 Bangladesh Cricket League]], with 34 dismissals in six matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=12743;type=tournament |title=Bangladesh Cricket League, 2018/19: Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was the leading wicket-taker for [[Prime Bank Cricket Club]] in the [[2018\u201319 Dhaka Premier Division Cricket League]] tournament, with 19 dismissals in 16 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12909;team=5189;type=tournament |title=Dhaka Premier Division Cricket League, 2018/19 - Prime Bank Cricket Club: Batting and bowling averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> He was the leading wicket-taker in the [[2019\u201320 National Cricket League]], with 31 dismissals in five matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=13404;type=tournament |title=National Cricket League, Most Wickets |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Debut years===\nRazzak was called into the [[Bangladeshi cricket team|Bangladesh national team]] for the 2004 [[Asia Cup]] [[One Day International]] tournament, making his debut against [[Hong Kong cricket team|Hong Kong]] in July.  He established himself as a regular fixture in the squad although he was not a regular in the starting eleven. He made his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in the second Test of the [[Australian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2005-06|Australian tour of Bangladesh]] in April 2006.\n\nAfter impressing in one-day cricket, he was called up for his Test debut at home to [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] at the [[Chittagong Divisional Stadium]]. [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]] batted first and he recorded 15 in his first Test match [[innings]]. A decent start but he failed to take a wicket in Australia's only innings and he registered a [[duck (cricket)|golden duck]] in an innings defeat. His next test appearance took place a year afterwards against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]] where he got first test wicket having [[Chamara Silva]] [[caught]]. He got [[Graeme Smith]] in a Test against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] and he got his highest Test match score of 33 in both innings, once finishing unbeaten. In a Test match against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], he registered his highest Test match bowling figures of 3\u201393. This and the next Test in the series (subsequently his last so far) brought his bowling action into question.\n\n===Suspension===\nFollowing [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008-09|New Zealand's tour of Bangladesh in October 2008]], Razzak was reported by umpires [[Daryl Harper]] and [[Asoka de Silva (cricketer)|Asoka de Silva]] for having a \"suspect bowling action\". This was the second time in his career that he had been reported for his bowling action. A bowler is deemed to have thrown the ball if his arm bends by more than 15&nbsp;degrees when [[delivery (cricket)|delivering]] the ball. It had been expected that only Razzak's quicker ball was suspect and he would be disallowed from bowling it,<ref>{{citation |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/376043.html |title=Razzak reported for suspect action |date=30 October 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2008-12-19}}</ref> however tests showed that Razzak bends his arm by 22\u201328 degrees, usually averaging 25&nbsp;degrees although his quicker ball was delivered at an average of 24&nbsp;degrees. As a result, Razzak was suspended from international cricket, although he is allowed to bowl under supervision in domestic cricket, until he remodels his action.<ref>{{citation |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/380284.html |title=Razzak suspended from bowling in international cricket |date=1 December 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2008-12-19}}</ref> In March 2009, the ICC lifted Razzak's suspension after he changed his bowling action; now both his stock delivery and faster ball are legal.<ref>{{citation |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/394939.html |title=ICC lifts Razzak's suspension |date=12 March 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Return after suspension===\nIn July 2009, on [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2009|Bangladesh's tour of the West Indies]], Razzak represented Bangladesh in international cricket for the first time since his suspension. Omitted from the Test squad, he was called up for the one-day series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/415028.html |title=Razzak joins ODI squad |date=18 July 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> Razzak's performance in the first One Day International, for which he was awarded the man-of-the-match award, helped Bangladesh defeat the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] by 52&nbsp;runs. He opened the bowling and took 4&nbsp;wickets for 39&nbsp;runs (4/39) against a West Indies side weakened by disputes between the players and the [[West Indies Cricket Board]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/416462.html |title=Razzak, Shakib seal Bangladesh win |first=Siddhartha |last=Talya |date=26 July 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/416326.html |title=Bangladesh look to build on Test success |first=Siddhartha |last=Talya |date=25 July 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> He finished as Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in the three match series, with 7&nbsp;wickets at 22.85, however he was injured in the final match. The [[hamstring]] strain he sustained while batting ruled him out of [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2009|Bangladesh's tour of Zimbabwe in August 2009]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/zimvbdesh2009/content/current/story/417401.html |title=Razzak ruled out of Zimbabwe series |date=2 August 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-08-06}}</ref> By the time Zimbabwe toured Bangladesh for a [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|five-match ODI series in October and November 2009]], Razzak had recovered from his injury and was included in the Bangladesh squad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/430712.html |title=Injured Mortaza out of Zimbabwe ODIs |date=22 October 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-11-07}}</ref> He took 15&nbsp;wickets in the series which Bangladesh won 4\u20131 and was named Man of the Series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/433122.html |title=We have great balance now&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib Al Hasan |date=5 November 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-11-07}}</ref>\n\n===Late career===\nAt the start of November 2010, the BCB announced 16&nbsp;central contracts. Razzak was one of six players in the top level.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/484743.html |title=Ashraful handed top-level central contract |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> He was included in Bangladesh's 15-man squad for the 2011 World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/497444.html |title=Mashrafe Mortaza not in World Cup squad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 January 2011 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> Zimbabwe returned to Test cricket in August 2011 with a one-off match against Bangladesh. Bangladesh lost the match, their first Test since touring England in June the previous year, with Razzak taking two wickets for 106&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-bangladesh-2011/content/current/story/523380.html |title=Uncapped Nasir, Shuvagoto in squad for Zimbabwe |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/332/332684.html |url-access=subscription |title=f53313 t2002 Zimbabwe v Bangladesh: Bangladesh in Zimbabwe 2011 (Only Test) |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2011-10-24}}</ref> In the subsequent five-match ODI series, Razzak was the least successful of the bowlers to deliver 20&nbsp;overs or more taking two wickets in four matches as Bangladesh lost the series 3\u20132.<ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6489;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in Zimbabwe ODI Series, 2011 / Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2011-10-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611234646/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6489%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=11 June 2015 }}</ref> When the West Indies toured in October he went wicketless in the ODI series and was subsequently dropped from the Test squad, which led him to consider the international retirement in 2014.<ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2011-10-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015050127/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=15 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/537022.html |title=Razzak dropped for West Indies Tests; Shafiul injured |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2013 he took 5 wickets against Sri Lanka in the 3rd ODI and became the 1st Bangladeshi bowler who took 200 wickets in ODI.<ref>{{cite news |title=Razzak first Bangladesh to grab 200 ODI wickets |url=http://www.dailyprimenews.com/details.php?id=8326 |newspaper=Prime News |date=28 March 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130410174506/http://www.dailyprimenews.com/details.php?id=8326 |archive-date=10 April 2013}}</ref> On 5 May 2013, at the 2nd ODI between [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] in Bulawayo, he scored his maiden half-century with 53* runs. At the same time, he achieved ''quickest half-century'' in cricket history of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-bangladesh-2013/content/story/634287.html |title=Career-best added bonus for Williams |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |access-date=6 May 2013}}</ref> But his team was defeated by 6 wickets. He is the first left arm spinner and 2nd spinner after [[Saqlain Mushtaq]] took a [[Hat-trick]].\n\nHowever, his milestone in first-class cricket to become the first Bangladeshi to take 500 wickets, he was added to the Bangladeshi Test squad as a cover for injured [[Shakib Al Hasan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/1134826.html |title=Razzak recalled for Tests after nearly four years | publisher=ESPNcricinfo| date=28 January 2018| accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> He made his comeback match [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2017\u201318|against Sri Lanka]] on 8 February 2018 and took 4 wickets to bowl out Sri Lanka for 222 in their first innings.<ref name=razzaqcomeback />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=56283}}\n\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Rangpur Riders squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Razzak, Abdur}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Khulna]]\n[[Category:Khulna Division cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khulna Royal Bengals cricketers]]\n[[Category:Royal Challengers Bangalore cricketers]]\n[[Category:One Day International hat-trick takers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Rangpur Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sylhet Sixers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kala Bagan Krira Chakra cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sheikh Jamal Dhanmondi Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh South Zone cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh under-23 cricketers]]\n[[Category:Agrani Bank Cricket Club cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzak Rajib}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Abdur Razzak <br /> \u0986\u09ac\u09cd\u09a6\u09c1\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09cd\u099c\u09be\u0995\n|               image = Adbur Razzak bowling 2010.jpg\n|             country = Bangladesh\n|            fullname = Abdur Razzak\n|            nickname = Raj\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1982|6|15|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Khulna]], Bangladesh\n|                role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = [[Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n|       international = true\n|   internationalspan = 2004\u20132018\n|       testdebutdate = 16 April\n|       testdebutyear = 2006\n|    testdebutagainst = Australia\n|             testcap = 45\n|        lasttestdate = 8 February\n|        lasttestyear = 2018\n|     lasttestagainst = Sri Lanka\n|        odidebutdate = 16 July\n|        odidebutyear = 2004\n|     odidebutagainst = Hong Kong\n|              odicap = 1\n|         lastodidate = 25 August\n|         lastodiyear = 2014\n|      lastodiagainst = West Indies\n|            odishirt = 41\n|       T20Idebutdate = 28 November\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2006\n|    T20Idebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n|             T20Icap = 1\n|        lastT20Idate = 27 August\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2014\n|     lastT20Iagainst = West Indies\n|               club1 = [[Khulna Division cricket team|Khulna Division]]\n|               year1 = 2001\u2013present\n|               club2 = [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]]\n|               year2 = 2008\n|               club3 = [[Rangpur Riders]]\n|               year3 = 2013\u2013present\n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 13\n|               runs1 = 245\n|            bat avg1 = 17.50\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 43\n|         deliveries1 = 2,817\n|            wickets1 = 28\n|           bowl avg1 = 59.75\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 4/63\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 4/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches2 = 153\n|               runs2 = 779\n|            bat avg2 = 13.43\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/1\n|          top score2 = 53[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries2 = 7,965\n|            wickets2 = 207\n|           bowl avg2 = 29.29\n|            fivefor2 = 4\n|             tenfor2 = 0\n|       best bowling2 = 5/29\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 32/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n|            matches3 = 34\n|               runs3 = 41\n|            bat avg3 = 4.10\n|           100s/50s3 = 0/0\n|          top score3 = 9\n|         deliveries3 = 730\n|            wickets3 = 44\n|           bowl avg3 = 19.04\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 4/16\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 10/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches4 = 128\n|               runs4 = 2,725\n|            bat avg4 = 17.58\n|           100s/50s4 = 0/10\n|          top score4 = 97\n|         deliveries4 = 34,708\n|            wickets4 = 581\n|           bowl avg4 = 28.95\n|            fivefor4 = 38\n|             tenfor4 = 10\n|       best bowling4 = 9/84\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 50/\u2013\n|                date = 4 May\n|                year = 2019\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/player/56283.html CricInfo\n}}\n'''Abdur Razzak''' ({{lang-bn|\u0986\u09ac\u09cd\u09a6\u09c1\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09cd\u099c\u09be\u0995}}; born 15 June 1982) is a Bangladeshi [[cricket]]er, who currently plays [[Test cricket]] and retired from [[Limited overs cricket|limited overs format]] of the game. Razzak is the first Bangladeshi to take 200 wickets in [[One Day International|ODIs]]. He is also the first left arm spinner and 2nd spinner after [[Saqlain Mushtaq]] took a [[Hat-trick]].\n\nHe made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut at Bangladeshi domestic level for Khulna Division in the 2001/02 season. Best known for being a tall [[left-arm orthodox spin]] bowler, he helped guide his division to the National Cricket Title in his maiden season. From there he was selected for Bangladesh A (training team for the full national squad) performing well against [[Zimbabwean cricket team|Zimbabwe A]], including figures of 7 for 17 in one game in [[Dhaka]].\n\nThough he has played just nine Tests, he has been more successful in [[One Day International]]s (ODIs) and was Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in the format in 2013, when he reached the 200 wickets milestone. <ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=2;id=25;type=team |title=Records / Bangladesh / One-Day Internationals / Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2011-10-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330230720/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?class=2%3Bid%3D25%3Btype%3Dteam |archivedate=30 March 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, he became the first Bangladesh player to take 500 wickets in first-class cricket.<ref name=first>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22131211/abdur-razzak-tushar-imran-climb-first-class-summits |title=Abdur Razzak and Tushar Imran climb first-class summits |author=Isam, Mohammad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 January 2018|date=17 January 2018 }}</ref> After four years, he made comeback to the Test squad on 8 February 2018 [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2017\u201318|against Sri Lanka]], taking 4-63 opening the bowling, but Bangladesh lost by 215 runs.<ref name=razzaqcomeback>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18527/report/1130745/bangladesh-vs-sri-lanka-2nd-test-sri-lanka-tour-of-bangladesh-2018 |title=Sri Lanka bat; Abdur Razzak returns after four years |author=Fernando, Andrew Fidel |publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> In November 2019, he took his 600th first-class wicket, becoming the first Bangladeshi bowler to reach the milestone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27987347/abdur-razzak-becomes-first-bangladeshi-bowler-bag-600-first-class-wickets |title=Abdur Razzak becomes first Bangladeshi bowler to bag 600 first-class wickets |author=Isam, Mohammad |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=2 November 2019 |accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n===Indian Premier League===\nRazzak was the only Bangladeshi to play in the [[2008 Indian Premier League]] making him the first Bangladeshi to play the league. He was bought for $50,000 by the [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]] and played in only one match. Despite not playing often for the team, Razzak believed that the experience he gained from the tournament was important. He stated that [[Anil Kumble]] \"was very helpful when I asked him about bowling in Test matches. He told me that given my bowling approach, it is very important to use variations within my line and length. Actually, captains would want a breakthrough from me so without using variations, wickets are hard to come by. Coach Venkatesh Prasad was also a great help\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/353083.html |title=Experience was more important than money&nbsp;\u2013 Razzak |date=31 May 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh domestic career===\nRazzak responded by taking his best bowling figures in first-class cricket (8/123). His match haul of 15/193 against [[Barisal Division cricket team|Barisal Division]] were the best in the history of the [[National Cricket League of Bangladesh|National Cricket League]], breaking the record set three years previously by [[Elias Sunny]], the bowler who had replaced Razzak in the Test team.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-domestic-2011/content/story/538053.html |title=Abdur Razzak's record-haul leads Khulna to win |first=Mohammad |last=Islam |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/537129.html |title=Ashraful must perform to play&nbsp;\u2013 Law |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-19}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, he was the leading wicket-taker in the [[2017\u201318 Bangladesh Cricket League]], with 43 dismissals in six matches, a record for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=12213;type=tournament |title=Bangladesh Cricket League 2017/18: Most Wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> He was also the leading wicket-taker in the [[2018\u201319 Bangladesh Cricket League]], with 34 dismissals in six matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=12743;type=tournament |title=Bangladesh Cricket League, 2018/19: Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was the leading wicket-taker for [[Prime Bank Cricket Club]] in the [[2018\u201319 Dhaka Premier Division Cricket League]] tournament, with 19 dismissals in 16 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12909;team=5189;type=tournament |title=Dhaka Premier Division Cricket League, 2018/19 - Prime Bank Cricket Club: Batting and bowling averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> He was the leading wicket-taker in the [[2019\u201320 National Cricket League]], with 31 dismissals in five matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=13404;type=tournament |title=National Cricket League, Most Wickets |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Debut years===\nRazzak was called into the [[Bangladeshi cricket team|Bangladesh national team]] for the 2004 [[Asia Cup]] [[One Day International]] tournament, making his debut against [[Hong Kong cricket team|Hong Kong]] in July.  He established himself as a regular fixture in the squad although he was not a regular in the starting eleven. He made his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in the second Test of the [[Australian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2005-06|Australian tour of Bangladesh]] in April 2006.\n\nAfter impressing in one-day cricket, he was called up for his Test debut at home to [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] at the [[Chittagong Divisional Stadium]]. [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]] batted first and he recorded 15 in his first Test match [[innings]]. A decent start but he failed to take a wicket in Australia's only innings and he registered a [[duck (cricket)|golden duck]] in an innings defeat. His next test appearance took place a year afterwards against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]] where he got first test wicket having [[Chamara Silva]] [[caught]]. He got [[Graeme Smith]] in a Test against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] and he got his highest Test match score of 33 in both innings, once finishing unbeaten. In a Test match against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], he registered his highest Test match bowling figures of 3\u201393. This and the next Test in the series (subsequently his last so far) brought his bowling action into question.\n\n===Suspension===\nFollowing [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008-09|New Zealand's tour of Bangladesh in October 2008]], Razzak was reported by umpires [[Daryl Harper]] and [[Asoka de Silva (cricketer)|Asoka de Silva]] for having a \"suspect bowling action\". This was the second time in his career that he had been reported for his bowling action. A bowler is deemed to have thrown the ball if his arm bends by more than 15&nbsp;degrees when [[delivery (cricket)|delivering]] the ball. It had been expected that only Razzak's quicker ball was suspect and he would be disallowed from bowling it,<ref>{{citation |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/376043.html |title=Razzak reported for suspect action |date=30 October 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2008-12-19}}</ref> however tests showed that Razzak bends his arm by 22\u201328 degrees, usually averaging 25&nbsp;degrees although his quicker ball was delivered at an average of 24&nbsp;degrees. As a result, Razzak was suspended from international cricket, although he is allowed to bowl under supervision in domestic cricket, until he remodels his action.<ref>{{citation |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/380284.html |title=Razzak suspended from bowling in international cricket |date=1 December 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2008-12-19}}</ref> In March 2009, the ICC lifted Razzak's suspension after he changed his bowling action; now both his stock delivery and faster ball are legal.<ref>{{citation |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/394939.html |title=ICC lifts Razzak's suspension |date=12 March 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Return after suspension===\nIn July 2009, on [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2009|Bangladesh's tour of the West Indies]], Razzak represented Bangladesh in international cricket for the first time since his suspension. Omitted from the Test squad, he was called up for the one-day series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/415028.html |title=Razzak joins ODI squad |date=18 July 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> Razzak's performance in the first One Day International, for which he was awarded the man-of-the-match award, helped Bangladesh defeat the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] by 52&nbsp;runs. He opened the bowling and took 4&nbsp;wickets for 39&nbsp;runs (4/39) against a West Indies side weakened by disputes between the players and the [[West Indies Cricket Board]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/416462.html |title=Razzak, Shakib seal Bangladesh win |first=Siddhartha |last=Talya |date=26 July 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/416326.html |title=Bangladesh look to build on Test success |first=Siddhartha |last=Talya |date=25 July 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> He finished as Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in the three match series, with 7&nbsp;wickets at 22.85, however he was injured in the final match. The [[hamstring]] strain he sustained while batting ruled him out of [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2009|Bangladesh's tour of Zimbabwe in August 2009]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/zimvbdesh2009/content/current/story/417401.html |title=Razzak ruled out of Zimbabwe series |date=2 August 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-08-06}}</ref> By the time Zimbabwe toured Bangladesh for a [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|five-match ODI series in October and November 2009]], Razzak had recovered from his injury and was included in the Bangladesh squad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/430712.html |title=Injured Mortaza out of Zimbabwe ODIs |date=22 October 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-11-07}}</ref> He took 15&nbsp;wickets in the series which Bangladesh won 4\u20131 and was named Man of the Series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/433122.html |title=We have great balance now&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib Al Hasan |date=5 November 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2009-11-07}}</ref>\n\n===Late career===\nAt the start of November 2010, the BCB announced 16&nbsp;central contracts. Razzak was one of six players in the top level.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/484743.html |title=Ashraful handed top-level central contract |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> He was included in Bangladesh's 15-man squad for the 2011 World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/497444.html |title=Mashrafe Mortaza not in World Cup squad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 January 2011 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref> Zimbabwe returned to Test cricket in August 2011 with a one-off match against Bangladesh. Bangladesh lost the match, their first Test since touring England in June the previous year, with Razzak taking two wickets for 106&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-bangladesh-2011/content/current/story/523380.html |title=Uncapped Nasir, Shuvagoto in squad for Zimbabwe |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/332/332684.html |url-access=subscription |title=f53313 t2002 Zimbabwe v Bangladesh: Bangladesh in Zimbabwe 2011 (Only Test) |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2011-10-24}}</ref> In the subsequent five-match ODI series, Razzak was the least successful of the bowlers to deliver 20&nbsp;overs or more taking two wickets in four matches as Bangladesh lost the series 3\u20132.<ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6489;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in Zimbabwe ODI Series, 2011 / Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2011-10-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611234646/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6489%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=11 June 2015 }}</ref> When the West Indies toured in October he went wicketless in the ODI series and was subsequently dropped from the Test squad, which led him to consider the international retirement in 2014.<ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2011-10-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015050127/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=15 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/537022.html |title=Razzak dropped for West Indies Tests; Shafiul injured |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2013 he took 5 wickets against Sri Lanka in the 3rd ODI and became the 1st Bangladeshi bowler who took 200 wickets in ODI.<ref>{{cite news |title=Razzak first Bangladesh to grab 200 ODI wickets |url=http://www.dailyprimenews.com/details.php?id=8326 |newspaper=Prime News |date=28 March 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130410174506/http://www.dailyprimenews.com/details.php?id=8326 |archive-date=10 April 2013}}</ref> On 5 May 2013, at the 2nd ODI between [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] in Bulawayo, he scored his maiden half-century with 53* runs. At the same time, he achieved ''quickest half-century'' in cricket history of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimbabwe-v-bangladesh-2013/content/story/634287.html |title=Career-best added bonus for Williams |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |access-date=6 May 2013}}</ref> But his team was defeated by 6 wickets. He is the first left arm spinner and 2nd spinner after [[Saqlain Mushtaq]] took a [[Hat-trick]].\n\nHowever, his milestone in first-class cricket to become the first Bangladeshi to take 500 wickets, he was added to the Bangladeshi Test squad as a cover for injured [[Shakib Al Hasan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/1134826.html |title=Razzak recalled for Tests after nearly four years | publisher=ESPNcricinfo| date=28 January 2018| accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> He made his comeback match [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2017\u201318|against Sri Lanka]] on 8 February 2018 and took 4 wickets to bowl out Sri Lanka for 222 in their first innings.<ref name=razzaqcomeback />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=56283}}\n\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Rangpur Riders squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Razzak, Abdur}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Khulna]]\n[[Category:Khulna Division cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khulna Royal Bengals cricketers]]\n[[Category:Royal Challengers Bangalore cricketers]]\n[[Category:One Day International hat-trick takers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Rangpur Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sylhet Sixers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kala Bagan Krira Chakra cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sheikh Jamal Dhanmondi Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh South Zone cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh under-23 cricketers]]\n[[Category:Agrani Bank Cricket Club cricketers]]\n", "name_user": "Mmitchell10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Update link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdur_Razzak_(cricketer)"}
{"title_page": "1987\u201388 DDR-Oberliga", "text_new": "{{infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[DDR-Oberliga]]\n| logo               = \n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| season             = 1987\u201388\n| winners            = [[BFC Dynamo]]\n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = [[FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt]]{{-}}[[Stahl Riesa]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[1988\u201389 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = BFC Dynamo\n| continentalcup2    = [[1988\u201389 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]{{-}}[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| matches            = 182\n| total goals        = 524\n| league topscorer   = [[Andreas Thom]] (20)<ref name=\"Lists\" >''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance         = 1,714,300<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance = 9,419<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason = [[1986\u201387 DDR-Oberliga|1986\u201387]]\n| nextseason = [[1988\u201389 DDR-Oberliga|1988\u201389]]\n}}\nThe '''1987\u201388 DDR-Oberliga''' was the 39th season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]].\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[Berliner FC Dynamo]] won the championship, the club's last of ten consecutive East German championships from 1978 to 1988. BFC Dynamo also won the [[FDGB-Pokal]], thereby becoming the second club after Dynamo Dresden to win the double in East Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref>\n\n[[Andreas Thom]] of BFC Dynamo was the league's top scorer with 20 goals,<ref name=\"Goal\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 25 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref> with Thom also taking the seasons [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|East German Footballer of the year]] award.<ref>''fuwo'', page: 92</ref>\n\nOn the strength of the 1987\u201388 title BFC Dynamo qualified for the [[1988\u201389 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out in an [[East Germany\u2013West Germany football rivalry|East-West German encounter]] by [[SV Werder Bremen]] in the first round. Sixth-placed club [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]] qualified for the [[1988\u201389 European Cup Winners' Cup]] as the seasons [[FDGB-Pokal]] runners-up and was knocked out by [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] second round. Second-placed [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] qualified for the [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup]] where it was knocked out by [[S.S.C. Napoli]] in the second round while third-placed [[Dynamo Dresden]] lost to [[VfB Stuttgart]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec198889.html |title= European Competitions 1988\u201389 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1987\u201388 season saw two newly promoted clubs, [[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]] and [[F.C. Hansa Rostock]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1987-1988-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR-Oberliga 1987\u201388|date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=}}</ref>\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|sortable_table=y\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=BER|name_BER=[[Berliner FC Dynamo]]\n|team2=LEI|name_LEI=[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|team3=DRE|name_DRE=[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n|team4=BRA|name_BRA=[[Stahl Brandenburg]]\n|team5=CHE|name_CHE=[[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]]\n|team6=CZJ|name_CZJ=[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n|team7=FCM|name_FCM=[[1. FC Magdeburg]]\n|team8=KMS|name_KMS=[[Chemnitzer FC|FC Karl-Marx-Stadt]]\n|team9=ROS|name_ROS=[[F.C. Hansa Rostock]]\n|team10=AUE|name_AUE=[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|BSG Wismut Aue]]\n|team11=UNI|name_UNI=[[1. FC Union Berlin]]\n|team12=RWE|name_RWE=[[FC Rot-Weiss Erfurt]]\n|team13=VOR|name_VOR=[[FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt]]\n|team14=RIE|name_RIE=[[Stahl Riesa]]\n|win_BER=15|draw_BER=7|loss_BER=4|gf_BER=59|ga_BER=30\n|win_LEI=14|draw_LEI=9|loss_LEI=3|gf_LEI=42|ga_LEI=21\n|win_DRE=12|draw_DRE=9|loss_DRE=5|gf_DRE=47|ga_DRE=24\n|win_BRA=12|draw_BRA=5|loss_BRA=9|gf_BRA=44|ga_BRA=37\n|win_CHE=7|draw_CHE=12|loss_CHE=7|gf_CHE=33|ga_CHE=33\n|win_CZJ=8|draw_CZJ=10|loss_CZJ=8|gf_CZJ=28|ga_CZJ=29\n|win_FCM=9|draw_FCM=7|loss_FCM=10|gf_FCM=34|ga_FCM=33\n|win_KMS=8|draw_KMS=9|loss_KMS=9|gf_KMS=40|ga_KMS=45\n|win_ROS=7|draw_ROS=9|loss_ROS=10|gf_ROS=42|ga_ROS=49\n|win_AUE=8|draw_AUE=7|loss_AUE=11|gf_AUE=24|ga_AUE=34\n|win_UNI=7|draw_UNI=8|loss_UNI=11|gf_UNI=35|ga_UNI=54\n|win_RWE=8|draw_RWE=5|loss_RWE=13|gf_RWE=40|ga_RWE=49\n|win_VOR=6|draw_VOR=9|loss_VOR=11|gf_VOR=33|ga_VOR=43\n|win_RIE=3|draw_RIE=10|loss_RIE=13|gf_RIE=23|ga_RIE=43\n\n|col_EC=green1|text_EC=League champion and qualified for the [[European Cup]]\n|result1=EC\n|col_UC=blue1|text_UC=Qualified for the [[UEFA Cup]]\n|result2=UC|result3=UC\n|col_CWC=yellow1|text_CWC=[[FDGB-Pokal]] runners-up and qualified for the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n|result6=CWC\n|col_R=red1|text_R=[[Promotion and relegation|Relegated]] to [[DDR-Liga]]\n|result13=R|result14=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=1991 |title= Das war unser Fu\u00dfball im Osten|trans-title= This was our football in the East|language=German |magazine= Fu\u00dfball-Woche (fuwo)|location=Berlin |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE|Axel-Springer-Verlag]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.f-archiv.de/ Das Deutsche Fussball Archiv] {{in lang|de}} Historic German league tables\n\n{{DDR-Oberliga seasons}}\n{{1987\u201388 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ddr-Oberliga 1987-88}}\n[[Category:1987\u201388 in German football leagues|Ober]]\n[[Category:DDR-Oberliga seasons|1987-88]]\n[[Category:1987\u201388 in East German football|1]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[DDR-Oberliga]]\n| logo                       = \n| image                      = \n| pixels                     = \n| caption                    = \n| season                     = 1987\u201388\n| winners                    = [[BFC Dynamo]]\n| promoted                   = \n| relegated                  = [[FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt]]{{-}}[[Stahl Riesa]]\n| continentalcup1            = [[1988\u201389 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = BFC Dynamo\n| continentalcup2           =  [[1988\u201389 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n| continentalcup3                = [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]{{-}}[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| matches                       = 182\n| total goals                     = 524\n| league topscorer           = [[Andreas Thom]] (20)<ref name=\"Lists\" >''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance                    = 1,714,300<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance      = 9,419<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason                 = [[1986\u201387 DDR-Oberliga|1986\u201387]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1988\u201389 DDR-Oberliga|1988\u201389]]\n}}\nThe '''1987\u201388 DDR-Oberliga''' was the 39th season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]].\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[Berliner FC Dynamo]] won the championship, the club's last of ten consecutive East German championships from 1978 to 1988. BFC Dynamo also won the [[FDGB-Pokal]], thereby becoming the second club after Dynamo Dresden to win the double in East Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref>\n\n[[Andreas Thom]] of BFC Dynamo was the league's top scorer with 20 goals,<ref name=\"Goal\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 25 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref> with Thom also taking the seasons [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|East German Footballer of the year]] award.<ref>''fuwo'', page: 92</ref>\n\nOn the strength of the 1987\u201388 title BFC Dynamo qualified for the [[1988\u201389 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out in an [[East Germany\u2013West Germany football rivalry|East-West German encounter]] by [[SV Werder Bremen]] in the first round. Sixth-placed club [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]] qualified for the [[1988\u201389 European Cup Winners' Cup]] as the seasons [[FDGB-Pokal]] runners-up and was knocked out by [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] second round. Second-placed [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] qualified for the [[1988\u201389 UEFA Cup]] where it was knocked out by [[S.S.C. Napoli]] in the second round while third-placed [[Dynamo Dresden]] lost to [[VfB Stuttgart]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec198889.html |title= European Competitions 1988\u201389 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1987\u201388 season saw two newly promoted clubs, [[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]] and [[F.C. Hansa Rostock]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1987-1988-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR-Oberliga 1987\u201388|date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=}}</ref>\n{{fb cl header|sort=y|winpoints=2}}\n|-style=\"background:#ddffdd\"\n||1||[[Berliner FC Dynamo]]||26||15||7||4||59||30||+29||37\n|-style=\"background:#fffacd\"\n||2||[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]||26||14||9||3||42||21||+21||37\n|-style=\"background:#fffacd\"\n||3||[[Dynamo Dresden]]||26||12||9||5||47||24||+23||33\n|-\n||4||[[Stahl Brandenburg]]||26||12||5||9||44||37||+7||29\n|-\n||5||[[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]]||26||7||12||7||33||33||0||26\n|-style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n||6||[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]||26||8||10||8||28||29||-1||26\n|-\n||7||[[1. FC Magdeburg]]||26||9||7||10||34||33||+1||25\n|-\n||8||[[Chemnitzer FC|FC Karl-Marx-Stadt]]||26||8||9||9||40||45||-5||25\n|-\n||9||[[F.C. Hansa Rostock]]||26||7||9||10||42||49||-7||23\n|-\n||10||[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|BSG Wismut Aue]]||26||8||7||11||24||34||-10||23\n|-\n||11||[[1. FC Union Berlin]]||26||7||8||11||35||54||