{"title_page": "John T. Houghton", "text_new": "{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Welsh physicist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Sir John T. Houghton\n|image             =John Houghton High Wycombe 20050226.jpg\n|image_size       =\n|caption           = Sir John Houghton speaking at a climate change conference in 2005\n|birth_name=John Theodore Houghton\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1931|12|30}}\n|birth_place       = [[Dyserth]], [[Denbighshire]], Wales\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|2020|4|15|1931|12|30|df=y}}\n|death_place       = \n|residence  = |citizenship = \n|nationality       = British\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Atmospheric physics]]\n|work_institutions = {{ublist | [[University of Oxford]] | [[Met Office]] }}\n|alma_mater        = [[Jesus College, Oxford]] <small>(B.A., 1951, M.A, 1955, PhD, 1955)</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Prof. Sir John Houghton \u2013 Brief biography |url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners-science-sirjohnhoughton.php |publisher=consejoculturalmundial.org |accessdate=8 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029233107/http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners-science-sirjohnhoughton.php |archivedate=29 October 2013 }}</ref>\n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = \n|author_abbrev_bot =|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = {{no wrap|[[The Chree Medal and Prize]] {{small|(1979)}}<br>[[Japan Prize]] {{small|(2006)}}<br>[[Albert Einstein World Award of Science]] {{small|(2009)}}}}\n|religion          = Christian\n|footnotes = |signature         =\n}}'''Sir John Theodore Houghton''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|FRS|FLSW}} (30 December 1931 \u2013 15 April 2020) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[atmospheric physics|atmospheric physicist]] who was the co-chair of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winning [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]]'s (IPCC) scientific assessment working group. He was the lead editor of first three IPCC reports. He was professor in [[atmospheric physics]] at the [[University of Oxford]], former Director General at the [[Met Office]] and founder of the [[Hadley Centre]].\n\nHe was the president of the John Ray Initiative, an organisation \"connecting Environment, Science and [[Christianity]]\",<ref>\"[http://www.jri.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=112&Itemid=83 DSc for JRI Chairman]\" at The John Ray Initiative website</ref> where he has compared the stewardship of the Earth, to the stewardship of the Garden of Eden by Adam and Eve.<ref>\"[http://www.jri.org.uk/brief/christianchallenge.htm The Christian Challenge of Caring for the Earth] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107115302/http://www.jri.org.uk/brief/christianchallenge.htm |date=7 November 2006 }}\" at The John Ray Initiative website</ref> He was a founding member of the [[International Society for Science and Religion]]. He was also the president of the [[Victoria Institute]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Dyserth]], he was the second of the three sons of Sidney and Vivien (n\u00e9e Yarwood) Houghton. His older brother, David (died 2015), became a meteorologist. <ref> https://rmets.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1002/wea.2566 </ref> The third and youngest brother, Paul Houghton, became a lecturer in engineering and was treasurer and company chairman of the John Ray Initiative, connecting the environment, science and Christianity.\n\nThe family moved to [[Rhyl]] when John was two, and he attended [[Rhyl High School|Rhyl Grammar School]] where he discovered his interest in science. He continued his education at [[Jesus College, Oxford]], gaining an MA (Oxon), MPhil and DPhil.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}<ref>http://www.japanprize.jp/en/prize_prof_2006_houghton.html</ref> He was brought up as an evangelical Christian by devout Christian parents and believed in science and Christianity as strengthening each other, as well as [[Christianity and environmentalism]]. Houghton's evangelical Christianity combined with his scientific background made him a significant voice in evangelical Christian circles. He was also an elder at [[Aberdyfi#presbyterian|Aberdovey Presbyterian Church]].\n\nIn 1962, Houghton married Dr Margaret Portman, daughter of a mill owner in Colwyn, Lancashire, and they had two children and seven grandchildren. Following her death from [[cancer]] in 1986, he set up the Margaret Houghton Memorial Fund, a research unit on medical nursing in her memory. His second wife, Sheila, became his companion for almost thirty years. \n\nHoughton was an Honorary Scientist of the [[Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research]] at the [[Met Office]] (since 2002); Honorary Scientist at the [[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]] (since 1991); a Trustee of the [[Shell Foundation]] (since 2000); Chairman of the John Ray Initiative (since 1997)<ref>http://www.japanprize.jp/en/prize_prof_2006_houghton.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Albert Einstein World Award of Science 2009|url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners/winners-of-the-world-award-of-science/prof-sir-john-houghton/|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref>Bio details heavily drawn from [http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/faraday/Advisory.php?UID=17 bio at the] [[Faraday Institute]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210053233/http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/faraday/Advisory.php?UID=17 |date=10 December 2007 }}</ref> and in 2013 was announced as an Advisory Board member for [[Sure Chill (refrigeration technology)|Sure Chill Technology]].\n\nAt various times, Sir John was\n* a Member of the UK Government Panel on Sustainable Development (1994\u20132000)\n* Chairman, [[Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution]] (1992\u201398)\n* Chairman or Co-Chairman, Scientific Assessment Working Group, [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (1988\u20132002)\n* Director General (later Chief Executive), UK [[Meteorological Office]] (1983\u201391)\n* Director Appleton, [[Science and Engineering Research Council]] (also Deputy Director, [[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]])(1979\u201383);\n* Professor of Atmospheric Physics, Oxford University (1976\u201383).\n*Principal Investigator for Space Experiments on NASA Spacecraft.\n\nHe was knighted in 1991. He moved back to Wales and {{when|date=June 2015}} lived in [[Aberdyfi]]. In 2007 he criticised the controversial documentary ''[[The Great Global Warming Swindle]]'' for its inaccuracies.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}} Sir John Houghton died of complications from [[COVID-19]] on 15 April 2020, aged 88.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/climate/news/2020-04-16-climate-scientist-founding-ipcc-editor-sir-john-houghton-dies|title=Sir John Houghton, Climate Scientist and Founding IPCC Editor, Dies at 88|date=16 April 2020|author=Bob Henson|website=The Weather Channel}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* [[Albert Einstein World Award of Science]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web|title=Albert Einstein World Award of Science 2009|url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners/winners-of-the-world-award-of-science/prof-sir-john-houghton/|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Japan Prize]] (2006)\n* [[International Meteorological Organization Prize]] (1999)\n* [[American Meteorological Society]], Honorary Member (1998)\n* [[Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]] (1995)\n* [[Global 500 Roll of Honour|Global 500 Award]], under the United Nations Environmental Programme (1994)\n* Climate Institute Annual Award (1992)\n* [[Bakerian Lecture]] of the [[Royal Society]], (1991);\n* [[Symons Gold Medal]], [[Royal Meteorological Society]] (1990)\n* [[Richard Glazebrook Medal and Prize]], [[Institute of Physics]], (1990);\n* [[William Gaskell Medal]] of the [[Royal Meteorological Society]], (1983)\n* [[The Chree medal and prize]] (1979)\n* President of the [[Royal Meteorological Society]] (1976\u20131978)\n* Elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (1972)\n\nHe received Honorary Doctorates of Science from the Universities of Wales (1991), Stirling (1992), East Anglia (1993), Leeds (1995), Heriot-Watt (1996), Greenwich (1997), Glamorgan (1998), Reading (1999), Birmingham (2000), Gloucestershire (2001), Hull (2002) and Dalhousie (2010). He was an Honorary Fellow of [[Jesus College, Oxford]] and of [[University of Wales, Lampeter]] and was also a Founding Fellow of the [[Learned Society of Wales]].\n\n==Legacy==\nA metal sculpture of Sir John Houghton was erected in [[Rhyl]] in 2013, together with figures of two other local celebrities, [[Don Spendlove]] and [[Mike Peters (musician)|Mike Peters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rhyljournal.co.uk/news/15720012.three-icons-of-rhyl-unveiled-at-entrance-to-harbour-bridge/|title=Three icons of Rhyl unveiled at entrance to harbour bridge|website=Rhyl, Prestatyn and Abergele Journal|date=8 October 2013|author=Matt Jones|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nHis publications include\n* Does God Play Dice? 1988, Intervarsity Press\n* Global Warming, the Complete Briefing, 1994, Lion Publishing (2nd edition 1997, Cambridge University Press; 3rd edition 2004, Cambridge University Press; 4th edition 2010, Cambridge University Press; 5th edition 2015, Cambridge University Press)\n* The search for God; can science help? 1995, Lion Publishing\n* Physics of Atmospheres, 1977. 2nd edition 1986, 3rd edition 2002, Cambridge University Press.\n* Climate Change, the IPCC Scientific Assessment, eds J.T. Houghton, G.J. Jenkins and J.J. Ephraums, 1990, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 1992, the Supplementary Report to the IPCC Scientific Assessment, eds. J.T. Houghton, B.A. Callander and S.K. Varney, 1992, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 1994, Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and an Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenarios, eds. J.T. Houghton, L.G. Meira Filho, J. Bruce, Hoesung Lee, B.A. Callander, E. Haites, N. Harris and K. Maskell, 1994, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 1995, the Science of Climate Change, eds. J.T. Houghton, L.G. Meira Filho, B.A.Callander, N. Harris, A. Kattenberg and K. Maskell, 1995, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 2001, The Scientific Basis, eds J.T. Houghton, Y. Ding, D.J. Griggs, M. Noguer, P.J. van der Linden, X. Dai, K. Maskell, C.A. Johnson, 2001 Cambridge University Press\n\n==Misquotation==\nIn a November 2006 article in Australia's [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|''The Daily Telegraph'']], journalist [[Piers Akerman]] quoted Houghton as saying \"Unless we announce disasters, no one will listen\", attributing the quotation to his 1994 book ''Global Warming, The Complete Briefing''.  This has since been quoted by many [[global warming scepticism|sceptics]], including [[Benny Peiser]] and [[Christopher Monckton, 3rd Viscount Monckton of Brenchley|Christopher Monckton]], and is listed at the top of the front page of [[Christopher Booker]]'s ''[[The Real Global Warming Disaster]]''.  However, the quotation does not appear in any edition of Houghton's book. Houghton never said any such thing and believed the opposite.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 10 February 2010\n | title = Fabricated quote used to discredit climate scientist\n | periodical = [[The Independent]]\n | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/climate-change/fabricated-quote-used-to-discredit-climate-scientist-1894552.html\n | accessdate = 10 February 2010\n}}\n</ref>\nThe publishers of ''The Real Global Warming Disaster'', The Continuum International Publishing Group, apologised for the reference to that quotation, confirmed (in addition to Booker's confirmation) that it will not be repeated, and agreed to place a corrigendum in any further copies of the book. In an article which appeared in ''The Sunday Telegraph'' on 20 February 2010, Christopher Booker purported to correct the misquotation contained in ''The Real Global Warming Disaster'' but this article contained yet further inaccuracies.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 20 February 2010\n | title = Article by Christopher Booker in ''The Sunday Telegraph'', \"What the weatherman never said\"\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/christopherbooker/7280369/What-the-weatherman-never-said.html\n | accessdate = 10 February 2010\n| work=The Daily Telegraph\n}}\n</ref> As a result, Houghton referred the matter to the Press Complaints Commission (PCC Reference 101959). Following the PCC's involvement, ''The Sunday Telegraph'' published on 15 August 2010 a letter of correction by Houghton stating his true position.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 15 August 2010\n | title = Letter by Sir John Houghton in The Sunday Telegraph, 15 August 2010\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/letters/7944874/Trident-shouldnt-lead-to-more-defence-cuts.html\n | accessdate = 9 January 2010\n| work=The Sunday Telegraph\n}}\n</ref> An article supportive of Houghton also appeared in the edition of 21 May 2010 of ''New Scientist''.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = May 2010\n \n | title = \"Living in denial: Unleashing a lie\", Jim Giles, ''New Scientist'', 21 May 2010\n | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20627606.300-living-in-denial-unleashing-a-lie.html\n | accessdate = 9 January 2010\n| work=New Scientist\n}}\n</ref>\n\nThe correct quotation was, \"If we want a good environmental policy in the future we'll have to have a disaster. It's like safety on public transport. The only way humans will act is if there's been an accident.\"<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 10 August 1995\n \n | title = 'Me and My God', Sir John Houghton talks to Frances Welch, 10 August 1995\n | url =  http://john-adams.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/houghton-and-god.pdf\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* \"[https://www.theguardian.com/life/opinion/story/0,,1284281,00.html Global warming is getting worse \u2013 but the message is getting through]\" (August 2004) and \"[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/green/comment/0,9236,1007302,00.html Global warming is now a weapon of mass destruction]\" (July 2003) from ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716210643/http://www.jri.org.uk/resource/climatechangeoverview.htm Overview of Climate Change, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041101173025/http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/cis/houghton/ Global warming \u2013 science, impacts and politics, lecture 2001]\n* [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmsctech/285/0031504.htm Evidence to Select Committee on Science and Technology, 2000]\n* [https://archive.is/20030225130933/http://www.lib.uci.edu/online/fellows/houghton.html Biography; publications list]\n\n{{Albert Einstein World Award of Science Laureates|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Houghton, John T}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Albert Einstein World Award of Science Laureates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Christians]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:British climatologists]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Learned Society of Wales]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change lead authors]]\n[[Category:Members of the International Society for Science and Religion]]\n[[Category:People from Rhyl]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Meteorological Society]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:Welsh physicists]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Europaea]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Welsh physicist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Sir John T. Houghton\n|image             =John Houghton High Wycombe 20050226.jpg\n|image_size       =\n|caption           = Sir John Houghton speaking at a climate change conference in 2005\n|birth_name=John Theodore Houghton\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1931|12|30}}\n|birth_place       = [[Dyserth]], [[Denbighshire]], Wales\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|2020|4|15|1931|12|30|df=y}}\n|death_place       = \n|residence  = |citizenship = \n|nationality       = British\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Atmospheric physics]]\n|work_institutions = {{ublist | [[University of Oxford]] | [[Met Office]] }}\n|alma_mater        = [[Jesus College, Oxford]] <small>(B.A., 1951, M.A, 1955, PhD, 1955)</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Prof. Sir John Houghton \u2013 Brief biography |url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners-science-sirjohnhoughton.php |publisher=consejoculturalmundial.org |accessdate=8 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029233107/http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners-science-sirjohnhoughton.php |archivedate=29 October 2013 }}</ref>\n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = \n|author_abbrev_bot =|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = {{no wrap|[[The Chree Medal and Prize]] {{small|(1979)}}<br>[[Japan Prize]] {{small|(2006)}}<br>[[Albert Einstein World Award of Science]] {{small|(2009)}}}}\n|religion          = Christian\n|footnotes = |signature         =\n}}'''Sir John Theodore Houghton''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|FRS|FLSW}} (30 December 1931 \u2013 15 April 2020) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[atmospheric physics|atmospheric physicist]] who was the co-chair of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winning [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]]'s (IPCC) scientific assessment working group. He was the lead editor of first three IPCC reports. He was professor in [[atmospheric physics]] at the [[University of Oxford]], former Director General at the [[Met Office]] and founder of the [[Hadley Centre]].\n\nHe was the president of the John Ray Initiative, an organisation \"connecting Environment, Science and [[Christianity]]\",<ref>\"[http://www.jri.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=112&Itemid=83 DSc for JRI Chairman]\" at The John Ray Initiative website</ref> where he has compared the stewardship of the Earth, to the stewardship of the Garden of Eden by Adam and Eve.<ref>\"[http://www.jri.org.uk/brief/christianchallenge.htm The Christian Challenge of Caring for the Earth] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107115302/http://www.jri.org.uk/brief/christianchallenge.htm |date=7 November 2006 }}\" at The John Ray Initiative website</ref> He was a founding member of the [[International Society for Science and Religion]]. He was also the president of the [[Victoria Institute]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Dyserth]], he was the second of the three sons of Sidney and Vivien (n\u00e9e Yarwood) Houghton. His older brother, David (died 2015), became a meteorologist. <ref> https://rmets.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1002/wea.2566 </ref> The third and youngest brother, Paul Houghton, became a lecturer in engineering and was treasurer and company chairman of the John Ray Initiative, connecting the environment, science and Christianity.\n\nThe family moved to [[Rhyl]] when John was two, and he attended [[Rhyl High School|Rhyl Grammar School]] where he discovered his interest in science. He continued his education at [[Jesus College, Oxford]], gaining an MA (Oxon), MPhil and DPhil.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}<ref>http://www.japanprize.jp/en/prize_prof_2006_houghton.html</ref> He was brought up as an evangelical Christian by devout Christian parents and believed in science and Christianity as strengthening each other, as well as [[Christianity and environmentalism]]. Houghton's evangelical Christianity combined with his scientific background made him a significant voice in evangelical Christian circles. He was also an elder at [[Aberdyfi#presbyterian|Aberdovey Presbyterian Church]].\n\nIn 1962, Houghton married Dr Margaret Portman, daughter of a mill owner in Colwyn, Lancashire, and they had two children and seven grandchildren. Following her death from [[cancer]] in 1986, he set up the Margaret Houghton Memorial Fund, a research unit on medical nursing in her memory. His second wife, Sheila, became his companion for almost thirty years. \n\nHoughton was an Honorary Scientist of the [[Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research]] at the [[Met Office]] (since 2002); Honorary Scientist at the [[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]] (since 1991); a Trustee of the [[Shell Foundation]] (since 2000); Chairman of the John Ray Initiative (since 1997)<ref>http://www.japanprize.jp/en/prize_prof_2006_houghton.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Albert Einstein World Award of Science 2009|url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners/winners-of-the-world-award-of-science/prof-sir-john-houghton/|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref>Bio details heavily drawn from [http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/faraday/Advisory.php?UID=17 bio at the] [[Faraday Institute]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071210053233/http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/faraday/Advisory.php?UID=17 |date=10 December 2007 }}</ref> and in 2013 was announced as an Advisory Board member for [[Sure Chill (refrigeration technology)|Sure Chill Technology]].\n\nAt various times, Sir John was\n* a Member of the UK Government Panel on Sustainable Development (1994\u20132000)\n* Chairman, [[Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution]] (1992\u201398)\n* Chairman or Co-Chairman, Scientific Assessment Working Group, [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (1988\u20132002)\n* Director General (later Chief Executive), UK [[Meteorological Office]] (1983\u201391)\n* Director Appleton, [[Science and Engineering Research Council]] (also Deputy Director, [[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]])(1979\u201383);\n* Professor of Atmospheric Physics, Oxford University (1976\u201383).\n*Principal Investigator for Space Experiments on NASA Spacecraft.\n\nHe was knighted in 1991. He moved back to Wales and {{when|date=June 2015}} lived in [[Aberdyfi]]. In 2007 he criticised the controversial documentary ''[[The Great Global Warming Swindle]]'' for its inaccuracies.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}} Sir John Houghton died of complications from [[COVID-19]] on 15 April 2020, aged 88.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://weather.com/news/climate/news/2020-04-16-climate-scientist-founding-ipcc-editor-sir-john-houghton-dies|title=Sir John Houghton, Climate Scientist and Founding IPCC Editor, Dies at 88|date=16 April 2020|author=Bob Henson|website=The Weather Channel}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* [[Albert Einstein World Award of Science]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web|title=Albert Einstein World Award of Science 2009|url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/winners/winners-of-the-world-award-of-science/prof-sir-john-houghton/|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Japan Prize]] (2006)\n* [[International Meteorological Organization Prize]] (1999)\n* [[American Meteorological Society]], Honorary Member (1998)\n* [[Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]] (1995)\n* [[Global 500 Roll of Honour|Global 500 Award]], under the United Nations Environmental Programme (1994)\n* Climate Institute Annual Award (1992)\n* [[Bakerian Lecture]] of the [[Royal Society]], (1991);\n* [[Symons Gold Medal]], [[Royal Meteorological Society]] (1990)\n* [[Richard Glazebrook Medal and Prize]], [[Institute of Physics]], (1990);\n* [[William Gaskell Medal]] of the [[Royal Meteorological Society]], (1983)\n* [[The Chree medal and prize]] (1979)\n* President of the [[Royal Meteorological Society]] (1976\u20131978)\n* Elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (1972)\n\nHe received Honorary Doctorates of Science from the Universities of Wales (1991), Stirling (1992), East Anglia (1993), Leeds (1995), Heriot-Watt (1996), Greenwich (1997), Glamorgan (1998), Reading (1999), Birmingham (2000), Gloucestershire (2001), Hull (2002) and Dalhousie (2010). He was an Honorary Fellow of [[Jesus College, Oxford]] and of [[University of Wales, Lampeter]] and was also a Founding Fellow of the [[Learned Society of Wales]].\n\n==Legacy==\nA metal sculpture of Sir John Houghton was erected in [[Rhyl]] in 2013, together with figures of two other local celebrities, [[Don Spendlove]] and [[Mike Peters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rhyljournal.co.uk/news/15720012.three-icons-of-rhyl-unveiled-at-entrance-to-harbour-bridge/|title=Three icons of Rhyl unveiled at entrance to harbour bridge|website=Rhyl, Prestatyn and Abergele Journal|date=8 October 2013|author=Matt Jones|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nHis publications include\n* Does God Play Dice? 1988, Intervarsity Press\n* Global Warming, the Complete Briefing, 1994, Lion Publishing (2nd edition 1997, Cambridge University Press; 3rd edition 2004, Cambridge University Press; 4th edition 2010, Cambridge University Press; 5th edition 2015, Cambridge University Press)\n* The search for God; can science help? 1995, Lion Publishing\n* Physics of Atmospheres, 1977. 2nd edition 1986, 3rd edition 2002, Cambridge University Press.\n* Climate Change, the IPCC Scientific Assessment, eds J.T. Houghton, G.J. Jenkins and J.J. Ephraums, 1990, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 1992, the Supplementary Report to the IPCC Scientific Assessment, eds. J.T. Houghton, B.A. Callander and S.K. Varney, 1992, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 1994, Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and an Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenarios, eds. J.T. Houghton, L.G. Meira Filho, J. Bruce, Hoesung Lee, B.A. Callander, E. Haites, N. Harris and K. Maskell, 1994, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 1995, the Science of Climate Change, eds. J.T. Houghton, L.G. Meira Filho, B.A.Callander, N. Harris, A. Kattenberg and K. Maskell, 1995, Cambridge University Press\n* Climate Change 2001, The Scientific Basis, eds J.T. Houghton, Y. Ding, D.J. Griggs, M. Noguer, P.J. van der Linden, X. Dai, K. Maskell, C.A. Johnson, 2001 Cambridge University Press\n\n==Misquotation==\nIn a November 2006 article in Australia's [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|''The Daily Telegraph'']], journalist [[Piers Akerman]] quoted Houghton as saying \"Unless we announce disasters, no one will listen\", attributing the quotation to his 1994 book ''Global Warming, The Complete Briefing''.  This has since been quoted by many [[global warming scepticism|sceptics]], including [[Benny Peiser]] and [[Christopher Monckton, 3rd Viscount Monckton of Brenchley|Christopher Monckton]], and is listed at the top of the front page of [[Christopher Booker]]'s ''[[The Real Global Warming Disaster]]''.  However, the quotation does not appear in any edition of Houghton's book. Houghton never said any such thing and believed the opposite.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 10 February 2010\n | title = Fabricated quote used to discredit climate scientist\n | periodical = [[The Independent]]\n | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/climate-change/fabricated-quote-used-to-discredit-climate-scientist-1894552.html\n | accessdate = 10 February 2010\n}}\n</ref>\nThe publishers of ''The Real Global Warming Disaster'', The Continuum International Publishing Group, apologised for the reference to that quotation, confirmed (in addition to Booker's confirmation) that it will not be repeated, and agreed to place a corrigendum in any further copies of the book. In an article which appeared in ''The Sunday Telegraph'' on 20 February 2010, Christopher Booker purported to correct the misquotation contained in ''The Real Global Warming Disaster'' but this article contained yet further inaccuracies.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 20 February 2010\n | title = Article by Christopher Booker in ''The Sunday Telegraph'', \"What the weatherman never said\"\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/christopherbooker/7280369/What-the-weatherman-never-said.html\n | accessdate = 10 February 2010\n| work=The Daily Telegraph\n}}\n</ref> As a result, Houghton referred the matter to the Press Complaints Commission (PCC Reference 101959). Following the PCC's involvement, ''The Sunday Telegraph'' published on 15 August 2010 a letter of correction by Houghton stating his true position.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 15 August 2010\n | title = Letter by Sir John Houghton in The Sunday Telegraph, 15 August 2010\n | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/letters/7944874/Trident-shouldnt-lead-to-more-defence-cuts.html\n | accessdate = 9 January 2010\n| work=The Sunday Telegraph\n}}\n</ref> An article supportive of Houghton also appeared in the edition of 21 May 2010 of ''New Scientist''.<ref>{{Citation\n | date = May 2010\n \n | title = \"Living in denial: Unleashing a lie\", Jim Giles, ''New Scientist'', 21 May 2010\n | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20627606.300-living-in-denial-unleashing-a-lie.html\n | accessdate = 9 January 2010\n| work=New Scientist\n}}\n</ref>\n\nThe correct quotation was, \"If we want a good environmental policy in the future we'll have to have a disaster. It's like safety on public transport. The only way humans will act is if there's been an accident.\"<ref>{{Citation\n | date = 10 August 1995\n \n | title = 'Me and My God', Sir John Houghton talks to Frances Welch, 10 August 1995\n | url =  http://john-adams.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/houghton-and-god.pdf\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* \"[https://www.theguardian.com/life/opinion/story/0,,1284281,00.html Global warming is getting worse \u2013 but the message is getting through]\" (August 2004) and \"[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/green/comment/0,9236,1007302,00.html Global warming is now a weapon of mass destruction]\" (July 2003) from ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716210643/http://www.jri.org.uk/resource/climatechangeoverview.htm Overview of Climate Change, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041101173025/http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/cis/houghton/ Global warming \u2013 science, impacts and politics, lecture 2001]\n* [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmsctech/285/0031504.htm Evidence to Select Committee on Science and Technology, 2000]\n* [https://archive.is/20030225130933/http://www.lib.uci.edu/online/fellows/houghton.html Biography; publications list]\n\n{{Albert Einstein World Award of Science Laureates|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Houghton, John T}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Albert Einstein World Award of Science Laureates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Christians]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:British climatologists]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Learned Society of Wales]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change lead authors]]\n[[Category:Members of the International Society for Science and Religion]]\n[[Category:People from Rhyl]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Meteorological Society]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]]\n[[Category:Welsh physicists]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Europaea]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Joseph2302", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy:dab fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_T._Houghton"}
{"title_page": "Land reform in Scotland", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{PoliticsScotland}}\n'''Land reform in Scotland''' is the ongoing process by which the ownership of land, its distribution and the law which governs it is modified, [[Land reform|reformed]] and modernised by [[Property law|property]] and [[Regulatory law|regulatory]] law.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=25 |language=English |date=2014 |quote=the Group defined land reform measures as provisions in an Act that reformed or modernised the rights of land ownership in Scotland, whether through property law or regulatory law.}}</ref>\n\n== Land ownership in Scotland ==\nScotland's land issues are rooted in two processes that happened in the 18th and 19th centuries, especially in the [[Scottish Highlands]]:\n* [[Enclosure]]s: landlords took control of the common lands under their regime, made them their private property, and excluded their tenants from using them.\n* [[Highland Clearances]]: many landlords forcefully evicted their tenant farmers from their lands, in order to use their lands for more profitable businesses. Other Gaels were transplanted to smaller plots on less productive land, or forced to leave by increasing rents. The Clearances created strong anti-landlord sentiments among the displaced and remaining inhabitants.<ref name=\"s06\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00291950500535251 |title=The great land debate and the Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 |journal=[[Norwegian Journal of Geography|Norsk Geografisk Tidsskrift \u2013 Norwegian Journal of Geography]] |volume=60 |pages=100\u2013109 |year=2007 |last1=Sellar |first1=W. David H.}}</ref>\n* A result of these processes was a severe [[concentration of land ownership]] that continues today. According to some estimates,<ref name=independent13>{{cite web |title=Imagine a feudal country where 432 families own half the land. Welcome to Scotland |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/imagine-a-feudal-country-where-432-families-own-half-the-land-welcome-to-scotland-8742545.html |accessdate=26 October 2016 |date=2013-08-01}}</ref> 432 families own half the private lands in Scotland, and just over 1200 landowners hold 2/3 of Scotland's lands.<ref name=bg07 />\n\nThe [[Crofters' Holdings (Scotland) Act 1886]] intended to protect the farmers' rights, but it was too weak to have any effect.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe Scotland land reform aims to balance the land-ownership situation by:\n* Securing the rights of access to common land,\n* Protecting the rights of tenants and small farmers, and\n* Helping small farmers and communities to buy land from large landowners.\n\n==Devolution and Labour Government (1997\u20132007)==\n{{See also|Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc. (Scotland) Act 2000|Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003}}\nIn 1997 a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Blair ministry|Government]] was elected to Westminster on a manifesto which included both devolution and land reform. Upon election, a Land Reform Policy Group (LRPG) was established under the chairmanship of [[Lord Sewel]], then [[Scottish Office]] Minister of State, who was also tasked with steering devolution legislation though the house of lords. Policy proposals and an extensive public consultation were published by the LRPG in 1999, the same year that the [[1999 Scottish Parliament election|first elections]] to the newly devolved Scottish parliament returned a Labour and Liberal Democrat coalition. Following the momentum of the 1997 and 1999 elections, devolution and the LRPG's proposals, land reform progressed rapidly in the [[1st Scottish Parliament|first session of the Scottish parliament]] with bills introduced to abolish Scotland's feudal land tenure system and a draft land reform bill introduced in 2000. The same year, the [[Scottish Land Fund]] was created and in 2001 began allocating its \u00a310 million budget of national lottery funding to assist rural communities to purchase land.<ref name=bg07 />\n\n=== Abolition of Feudal Tenure ===\nThe first piece of land reform legislation in the 21st century, the [[Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc. (Scotland) Act 2000]] was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 3 May 2000 and received royal assent on 9 June the same year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc. (Scotland) Act 2000 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2000/5/pdfs/asp_20000005_en.pdf |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=1 |language=en |quote=The Bill for this Act of the Scottish Parliament was passed by the Parliament on 3rd May 2000 and received Royal Assent on 9th June 2000.}}</ref> The act formed the core of a three part reform of Scottish property law, alongside the [[Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003]] and [[Tenements (Scotland) Act 2004]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=142 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref> The main provisions of the act included the abolition of feudal superiorities and tenure, to be replaced by a system of outright ownership in which those who had been vassals became outright owners. This necessitated the extinction of superiors\u2019 rights to collect feu duties, for which they were entitled to compensation in the form of a single payment of a size that, when invested at an annual rate of 2.5%, would yield interest equal to the former feu duty.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Guide to the Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc (Scotland) Act 2000 & the Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003 for Housing Associations |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/Doc/17002/0025016.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Executive |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=31 |date=2004 |quote=The formula is set out in section 4 of the 1974 Act \u2013 it requires payment of \u201csuch a sum of money as would, if invested in 2\u00bd per cent. Consolidated Stock at the middle market price at the close of business last preceding the date occurring one month before the said term, produce an annual sum equal to the feuduty\u201d.}}</ref> However, as Scotland's remaining feu duties had been fixed many years previously, inflation meant that by the time of the act's passing their value was, in most cases, effectively nominal.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wightman |first1=Andy |title=The Poor Had No Lawyers |date=2013 |publisher=Birlinn}}</ref> The act also extinguished superiors\u2019 rights to enforce real burdens, conditions on the holding of land, retaining only those conditions enforceable by neighbouring land owners or by certain legal bodies on public policy grounds. The legal basis of real burdens and title conditions was then reformulated in the Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/9/pdfs/asp_20030009_en.pdf |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> The end of feudal tenure simplified titles to land, while the subsequent Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003 modernised the types of interests and conditions that can be attached to those titles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=28 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref> Finally, common law surrounding tenements was then reformed in light of these changes under the Tenements (Scotland) Act 2004, completing the abolition of Scotland's feudal property system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=142 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n=== The 2003 Acts ===\n2003 saw two important pieces of legislation make their way through the Scottish parliament; the [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003|Land Reform (Scotland) Act]] and the Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act. The Land Reform (Scotland) Act has three parts, with provisions regarding three areas of land rights in Scotland; the creation of a legal framework for [[Freedom to roam|land access]], the community right to buy and crofting community right to buy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/2/pdfs/asp_20030002_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> The first part formalises the tradition in Scotland of unhindered access to open countryside. It creates a framework for responsible access to land and inland water,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/2/notes/division/2 |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 \u2013 Explanatory Notes |publisher=Legislation.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-10-31}}</ref> provided that care was taken not to cause damage or interfere with activities including farming and game stalking. Access rights apply to any non-motorised activities, including walking, cycling, horse-riding and wild camping. They also allow access on inland water for canoeing, rowing, sailing and swimming. This aspect of the Act follows the distinctive approach set out in the [[Scottish Outdoor Access Code]], specifying the rights and responsibilities of land managers, countryside users and recreational managers.<ref>{{cite web |ssrn=1673225 |title=Progressive Property in Action: The Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 by John A. Lovett :: SSRN |publisher=Papers.ssrn.com |date= }}</ref> Similar legislation was passed for [[England]] and [[Wales]] with the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/37/pdfs/ukpga_20000037_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe second part of the act establishes the community right to buy, allowing communities with populations of up to 10,000 to register an interest in land, entitling them to first right of refusal should the owner put the land up for sale or intend to transfer ownership, provided a representative community body can be formed to carry out the purchase.\n\nFinally, the third part establishes the crofting community right to buy which allows crofting communities to purchase crofts and associated land from existing landowners. It differs from the community right to buy in that it can be exercised at any time, regardless of whether the land has been put on the market, allowing crofting communities to purchase land even in the absence of a willing seller.\n\nThe Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act 2003 amends the law relating to agricultural holdings under the Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act 1991. It provides for new forms of agricultural tenancies and makes provision in relation to these tenancies, the right of certain agricultural tenants to buy land and the use of certain agricultural land for non-agricultural purposes. It makes special provision for certain agricultural tenancies where the tenant is a partnership and for the resolution of disputes between landlords and tenants arising under agricultural tenancies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act 2003 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/11/pdfs/asp_20030011_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==SNP Government (2007\u2013present)==\n{{See also|Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015|Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016}}\nThe May [[2007 Scottish Parliament election]] resulted, for the first time, in a [[Scottish National Party]] [[minority government]]. The first term of SNP government was marked by a lack of action on land reform. However, following re-election in [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011]], this time with a parliamentary majority, land reform returned to the government agenda with the Scottish Government establishing the '''Land Reform Review Group''' in 2012 and First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] in 2013 announcing a target of seeing 1 million acres of land in community ownership by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=1 million acres short life working group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Environment/land-reform/MillionAcres |website=The Scottish Government |accessdate=26 March 2017}}[[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This content is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/ Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref> The Land Reform Review Group was given the task of identifying how land reform would enable rural and urban communities to have a stake in the ownership, governance, management and use of land, assist in the acquisition and management of that land and promote new relationships between land, people, economy and environment in Scotland. Its final report, published in May 2014, recommended policies to modernise and diversify land ownership in Scotland and encourage sustainable development, some of which would form the basis of the [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015]] and [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016]]. During this period the Land Registration etc. (Scotland) Act 2012 introduced changes to the [[conveyancing]] system in Scotland, with the aim of having all land in Scotland registered under the [[Registers of Scotland|Land Register of Scotland]] within 10 years. Prior to the act, entry of land into the register would be prompted by a sale but other transfers of land would not prompt first entry. The act expanded the triggers for first entry to include any transfer of property or the signing of a long lease in order to accelerate the transition from the antiquated deed based Register of Sassines to the modernised map based Land Register.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gamba |first1=Stephen |title=The Land Registration (Scotland) Act 2012 \u2013 a brief guide |url=http://www.gillespiemacandrew.co.uk/media/321190/gillespie-macandrew-land-reform-scotland-bill-2015-a-brief-guide.pdf |publisher=Gillespie MacAndrew LLP |accessdate=26 March 2017 |date=17 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===The Salvesen v Riddell case (2012\u20132013)===\nIn 2012, a section of the Agricultural Holdings Act was challenged and suspended by the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|UK Supreme Court]].<ref name=svr13>{{cite web |title=Salvesen v Riddell and another, Lord Advocate intervening (Scotland) |url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/uksc-2012-0111.html |author=Lord Hope, Lord Kerr, Lord Wilson, Lord Reed, Lord Toulson |publisher=Uk Supreme Court |accessdate=31 October 2016 |date=24 April 2013}}</ref> The trigger for this ruling was an appeal by Salvesen, the owner of Peaston Farm near [[Ormiston]]. The Riddells were tenants in this farm and Section 72 of the 2003 Act greatly restricted the ability of landowners to terminate the tenancies of their tenants. Initially, the start date of this restriction was set to 4 February 2003. This led many landlords, including Salvesen, to terminate the tenancies of their tenants the day before \u2013 3 February 2003. A later amendment to section 72 retroactively set the start date of the restrictions to 16 September 2002, which made Salvesen's termination notice ineffective.\n\nSalvesen applied to the [[Scottish Land Court|Land Court]], which repealed his application. He then appealed to the Court of Session and obtained permission to apply to the UK Supreme Court. His main claim was that Section 72 is incompatible with his property rights, the rights guaranteed to him by [[Article 1 of the European Convention on Human Rights]]. The  Supreme  Court  unanimously  allowed  the  appeal.  It  found  that  Mr.  Salvesen's  A1P1  rights  were  violated  by section  72(10)  of  the  2003  Act  and  that  the  provision  was  outside  the  legislative  competence  of  the  Scottish  Parliament under the [[Scotland Act 1998]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The legal status of unlawful legislation: Salvesen v Riddell [2013] UKSC 22 |url=https://publiclawforeveryone.com/2013/04/25/the-legal-status-of-unlawful-legislation-salvesen-v-riddell-2013-uksc-22/ |date=2013-04-25 |author=Mark Eliott}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The case that keeps surprising \u2013 Salvesen v Riddell |url=http://www.brodies.com/blog/case-keeps-surprising-salvesen-v-riddell/ |accessdate=31 October 2016 |author=Gemma Mckinlay |date=2015-01-29}}</ref>\n\n===Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015===\nThe [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015]], marked the first major piece of land reform legislation to be passed under the SNP government. Its provisions covered different areas pertaining to community empowerment and public participation in policy and planning, including several related directly to land.<ref>{{cite web |title=Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act FAQs |url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/People/engage/CommunityEmpowermentBillFAQs |website=Scottish Government |accessdate=23 March 2017}} [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This content is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/ Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref> The most important of these was the extension of the Community Right to Buy to communities of any size, including, for the first time, those in urban areas. It also introduced a new community right to buy land which is abandoned, neglected or causing harm to the environmental wellbeing of the community. Similar to the 2003 Act's crofting community right to buy, this new right does not require a willing seller. Rather, Scottish ministers may compel a landowner to sell to communities with a registered interest, if they deem the sale likely to contribute to sustainable local development.\n\nFurther provisions granted community bodies the right to request to purchase, lease, manage or use land and buildings held by local authorities, Scottish ministers and other Scottish public bodies, of which relevant authorities are required to create and maintain a publicly available register. The Act reformed [[Common Good Fund|Common Good Property]], requiring local authorities to establish and maintain registers of all common good property held by them and to inform and consult local community bodies before any change of use or disposal of common good property. Allotments, updates and simplifies legislation on allotments.\n\nIt also set a requirement for local authorities to take steps to provide [[Allotment (gardening)|allotments]] should waiting lists exceed certain lengths and strengthened protections for allotments, regulated rents and allowed tenants to sell food produced on allotments on a not for profit basis. The act required that local authorities develop food growing strategies, including the identification of land that may be used as allotment sites or potential land for community cultivation.\n\nIt has been found that the Scottish approach to [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015|community empowerment and localism]] marks an example of policy divergence from the rest of the UK<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rolfe |first1=Steve |title=Divergence in Community Participation Policy: Analysing Localism and Community Empowerment Using a Theory of Change Approach |journal=Local Government Studies |volume=42 |pages=97\u2013118 |doi=10.1080/03003930.2015.1081848 |year=2016 |hdl=1893/23241 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> but that significant challenges remain in how to ensure a shared strategy; shared resources; and shared accountability.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Elliott |first1=Ian |last2=Fejszes |first2=Violetta |last3=T\u00e0rrega |first3=Mariola |title=The Community Empowerment Act and localism under devolution in Scotland: The perspective of multiple stakeholders in a council ward |journal=International Journal of Public Sector Management |doi=10.1108/IJPSM-03-2018-0080 |year=2018 |url=http://nrl.northumbria.ac.uk/36095/1/Elliott%20et%20al%20-%20The%20Community%20Empowerment%20Act%20and%20Localism%20under%20Devolution%20in%20Scotland%20AAM.pdf }}</ref>\n\n===Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016===\nIn 2013 [[Richard Lochhead]], then [[Cabinet Secretary for the Rural Economy and Connectivity|Cabinet Secretary for Rural Affairs and the Environment]], announced the launch of the Agricultural Holdings Review, which would examine the situation of land ownership and use, tenant-owner relationships, and all of the relevant legislation. The Review published its final report in January 2015, and the recommendations were put out to consultation.\n<ref name=\"review\">{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date=January 2015 |title=Review of Agricultural Holdings Legislation Final Report |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0046/00468852.pdf |publisher=Scottish Government |format=PDF |location=Edinburgh |access-date=25 April 2017 |quote=&nbsp;}}</ref><ref name=\"consultation\">{{cite web |last1=Land Reform Team |title=A Consultation on the future of Land Reform in Scotland |url=https://consult.scotland.gov.uk/land-reform-and-tenancy-unit/land-reform-scotland |year=2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the responses to the consultation the [[Scottish Government]] presented the ''Land Reform (Scotland) Bill'' to the [[Scottish Parliament]] on 22 June 2015. The Bill was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 16 March 2016, and received Royal Assent on 22 March 2016 becoming [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016]].<ref name=\"bill-parliament\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/Bills/90675.aspx |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Bill |date=18 June 2015 |website=www.parliament.scot |access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref> The most radical and controversial provision of the act was the creation of the Community Right to Buy for Sustainable Development. This permitted [[Scottish Ministers]] to approve the purchase of privately owned land by a community body with a registered interest. Like the Crofting Community Right to Buy and the Community Right to Buy abandoned or derelict land, the Community Right to Buy for Sustainable Development does not require a willing seller but allows ministers to compel landowners to sell if they decide that the sale will further sustainable development in the area.<ref>{{cite web |title=Community rights to buy in Scotland \u2013 which is which, and what are they for? |url=http://www.brodies.com/node/8185 |website=Brodies |accessdate=5 March 2017 |language=en}}</ref> Community bodies may also register an interest in allowing a third party to purchase land on the same basis.\n\nThis new Community Right to Buy was not the only provision of the Act. The Act required that the Scottish Government produce a 'Land Rights and Responsibilities Statement', setting out its objectives for land reform and to establish a [[Scottish Land Commission]] to take forward the land reform process and prepare a strategic plan, for the approval of [[Scottish Ministers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blair |first1=Mike |title=A Brief Guide to Land Reform in Scotland |url=http://www.gillespiemacandrew.co.uk/media/340813/land-reform-act-2016.pdf |publisher=Gillespie Macandrew LLP |accessdate=5 March 2017 |date=April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306131212/http://www.gillespiemacandrew.co.uk/media/340813/land-reform-act-2016.pdf |archive-date=6 March 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other provisions of the act included new regulations to require persons who control land to be identified, with information obtained to appear in the Land Register of Scotland; the removal of sporting rights exemption from rates, are to be re-valued; and further powers for [[Scottish Natural Heritage]] to control deer management. It also makes provision for notice and consultation where core paths are to be amended.<ref>{{cite web |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2016/18/pdfs/asp_20160018_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nFurther provisions of the Act pertain to agricultural tenancies including new protections for tenant farmers against eviction, the introduction of a modernised limited duration tenancy with greater rights for tenants relative to landowners and the widening of eligible assignees and inheritors of tenancies. Additionally, tenants under the 1991 Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act are now presumed to have registered their right to buy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scottish farmer facing eviction wins last-minute reprieve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/nov/26/scottish-farmer-facing-eviction-wins-last-minute-reprieve |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=guardian16>{{cite web |title=A new dawn for land reform in Scotland? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/scotland-blog/2016/mar/17/a-new-dawn-for-land-reform-in-scotland |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Holyrood approves sweeping Scottish land reforms |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3b4234da-eb55-11e5-bb79-2303682345c8 |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n=== Criticism by landlords ===\nIn August 2013, landowners including the [[Duke of Roxburghe]] expressed concerns about the work of the Land Reform Review Group and the focus on community ownership. The landowners stated that private ownership brought efficiency and greater protection for [[endangered species]] from development of land. Also, there were other social, economic, and environmental benefits to private ownership of Scottish land. The Duke of Roxburghe raised concerns specifically about the economic impacts, and the impact on the agricultural sector, saying:\n{{Quote|Radical proposals that threaten private property rights and which impact adversely on private enterprise, investment and development or which deprive young aspiring farmers the opportunity to get a firm foothold on the farming ladder would be immensely damaging in our view and act against the interests of the communities involved.|Duke of Roxburghe|August 2013, quoted in ''[[The Scotsman]]'' newspaper|<ref name=\"scotsman-2013-august\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/lairds-warn-holyrood-over-new-land-buy-out-powers-1-3023862 |title=Lairds warn Holyrood over new land buy-out powers |website=www.scotsman.com |language=en |date=1 August 2013 |access-date=27 April 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nMany other landlords opposed the passage of the Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016. Mark Coombs, the estate manager of the {{convert|33,000|ha|acre|abbr=on}} Queensberry Estate, owned by the [[Duke of Buccleuch|10th Duke of Buccleuch]], stated that \"there are also concerns if the purpose of changing the ownership is simply to allow another party \u2026 to carry out the same activity as is currently being undertaken by the existing owner as this strikes at the essence of ownership rights and suggests a clear move towards a more collectivist political view which is not representative of the body politic of Scotland.\" Thus hurting the property rights of the landowners since it strips them of control of their property.<ref name=independent13 />\n\nDavid Johnstone, chairman of Scottish Land and Estates, said the proposal could lead to land not being made available to let, and hurting the tenant farming sector. Johnstone said: \"What you are doing is giving a tenant a stake in the capital value of the farm. If the landlord doesn\u2019t have the ability to pay, then the farm never comes back... That has got to have a knock on effect in the confidence of anyone who might wish to come to let land or is letting land at the moment.\"<ref name=telegraph15>{{cite news |last1=Auslan Cramb |title=Property rights threatened by 'aggressive' change in land reform bill |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/earth/countryside/12057440/Property-rights-threatened-by-aggressive-change-in-land-reform-bill.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=31 October 2016 |date=2015-12-18}}</ref>\n\nSeafield and Strathspey Estates argued that land concentration is not a bad thing, as it may lead to more efficient management. Seafield and Strathspey Estates is a {{convert|35,000|ha|acre|abbr=on}} enterprise which includes salmon beats on the [[River Spey]], and is managed on behalf of the family of the [[Earl of Seafield]]. It said landowners were being blamed for the inefficiencies of local and central government. \"There is a myth presented by individuals sponsoring land reform in Scotland that 'too many acres are owned by too few individuals.' It may be true that 'many acres are owned by few individuals' but there is very little evidence presented to show that this is a bad thing\".<ref name=independent13 />\n\n=== Criticism by Scottish Parliament ===\nThe Land Reform (Scotland) Bill was criticised during its passage by the [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|Delegated Powers and Law Reform Committee]] of the Scottish Parliament on the basis that it granted a significant power to [[Scottish Ministers|Scottish Minister]] to implement much of the details of the Act through [[Scottish Statutory Instrument|secondary legislation]] and delegated powers. Turcan Connell identified concerns around the implementation of the Act and the amount of scrutiny the detailed law would receive.<ref name=\"turcan-connell\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.turcanconnell.com/media/constitutional-issues/scottish-land-reform/articles/2016/04/land-reform-update-april-2016/ |title=Land Reform Update \u2013 April 2016 |date=27 April 2016 |website=Turcan Connell |publisher=Turcan Connell |language=en |access-date=25 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426055558/https://www.turcanconnell.com/media/constitutional-issues/scottish-land-reform/articles/2016/04/land-reform-update-april-2016/ |archive-date=26 April 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Recommendations by legal experts ===\nSeveral parts of the Bill have been criticized as follows:<ref name=ms15>{{cite journal |doi=10.2139/ssrn.2698578 |title=The Land Reform (Scotland) Bill and Human Rights: Key Points and Recommendations |year=2015 |last1=MacInnes |first1=Megan |last2=Shields |first2=Kirsteen}}</ref>\n* The criteria for community buyout (s.47) is too demanding. There are double criteria: significant benefit from the transfer, and significant harm from non-transfer. Each one of these criteria alone should be sufficient.\n* The upper bound of 10 years on tenancy (part 10, s.74) is too short and hurts the rights of the tenants.\n* The paragraphs on transparency and accountability (parts 3-4, s.35-36) are too weak: there are no sanctions on refusing to give information about the landowner, and there is no obligation to give information on the real person owning the land (the real landowner often hides behind a \"shell company\").\n\nLand-reform activists claim that the current reform is insufficient as several important amendments were voted down by SNP and Conservative backbenchers, including:<ref name=guardian16 />\n* Land cap \u2013 restricting the amount of land that one individual can own.\n* Preventing land ownership via offshore tax havens. Andy Wightman, the land reform spokesperson for the Scottish Greens and MSP candidate for Lothian, revealed that companies owned by the Buccleuch Estates used tax havens in the Cayman Islands. He said that \"The Green bid to clamp down on the use of tax havens goes to the heart of understanding who owns Scotland. As we have seen this week with the uncovering of the complex corporate affairs of the Buccleuch Estates, there is an urgent need to ensure transparency in who profits from Scottish land.\"\n\n=== Criticism by PhD students ===\nIn a 2016 article in the journal of the [[Law Society of Scotland]], Douglas Maxwell claims the Land Reform (Scotland) Bill contains poorly-defined terms such as \"sustainable development\" and \"communities\" which may place the bill in conflict with international human rights laws, particularly the [[ECHR]] [[Protocol 1, article 1]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Douglas Maxwell |title=Human rights and land reform: unanswered questions |url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/Magazine/61-1/1021198.aspx |date=2016-01-18}}</ref>\n\n== Community focus ==\nLand reform in Scotland is unusual in its emphasis on [[community ownership|community land ownership]], with the Scottish government adopting the target of seeing 1 million acres of land under community ownership by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=One Million Acres by 2020 \u2013 Strategy report and recommendations from the 1 Million Acre Short Life Working Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Publications/2015/12/5735 |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=6 March 2017 |date=2015}}</ref><ref name=bg07>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2005.09.004 |title=Community-based land reform: Lessons from Scotland |journal=Land Use Policy |volume=24 |pages=24\u201334 |year=2007 |last1=Bryden |first1=John |last2=Geisler |first2=Charles}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2012.07.013 |title=Why community ownership? Understanding land reform in Scotland |journal=Land Use Policy |volume=31 |pages=289\u2013297 |year=2013 |last1=Hoffman |first1=Matthew}}</ref> Most other land reforms have focused on giving land ownership rights to individual farmers. In contrast, the Land Reform (Scotland) Acts of 2003 and 2016 grant a collective right-to-buy to entire communities living in a geographical area.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Scottish Land Court]]\n* [[Lands Tribunal for Scotland]]\n* [[Registers of Scotland]]\n* [[Scottish Land Restoration League]]\n* [[Highland Land League]]\n* [[Scottish Land Fund]]\n* [[List of community buyouts in Scotland]]\n* [[Right of public access to the wilderness]]\n* [[Community ownership]]\n* [[Community Land Scotland]]\n* [[Land raid]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gov.scot/Topics/farmingrural/Rural/rural-land Rural land] on Scottish Government website\n* [http://www.outdooraccess-scotland.com/the-act-and-the-code/introduction Scottish Outdoor Access Code] on www.outdooraccess-scotland.com\n* [http://www.mcofs.org.uk/know-the-code.asp The Mountaineering Council of Scotland \u2014 Know the Code]\n* {{UK-LEG|path=asp/2003/2|title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003|type=asp}}\n\n{{Sustainable development in Scotland}}\n{{Jacobitism}}\n{{UK legislation}}\n\n[[Category:Land reform in Scotland| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{PoliticsScotland}}\n'''Land reform in Scotland''' is the ongoing process by which the ownership of land, its distribution and the law which governs it is modified, [[Land reform|reformed]] and modernised by [[Property law|property]] and [[Regulatory law|regulatory]] law.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=25 |language=English |date=2014 |quote=the Group defined land reform measures as provisions in an Act that reformed or modernised the rights of land ownership in Scotland, whether through property law or regulatory law.}}</ref>\n\n== Land ownership in Scotland ==\nScotland's land issues are rooted in two processes that happened in the 18th and 19th centuries, especially in the [[Scottish Highlands]]:\n* [[Enclosure]]s: landlords took control of the common lands under their regime, made them their private property, and excluded their tenants from using them.\n* [[Highland Clearances]]: many landlords forcefully evicted their tenant farmers from their lands, in order to use their lands for more profitable businesses. Other Gaels were transplanted to smaller plots on less productive land, or forced to leave by increasing rents. The Clearances created strong anti-landlord sentiments among the displaced and remaining inhabitants.<ref name=\"s06\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00291950500535251 |title=The great land debate and the Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 |journal=[[Norwegian Journal of Geography|Norsk Geografisk Tidsskrift \u2013 Norwegian Journal of Geography]] |volume=60 |pages=100\u2013109 |year=2007 |last1=Sellar |first1=W. David H.}}</ref>\n* A result of these processes was a severe [[concentration of land ownership]] that continues today. According to some estimates,<ref name=independent13>{{cite web |title=Imagine a feudal country where 432 families own half the land. Welcome to Scotland |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/imagine-a-feudal-country-where-432-families-own-half-the-land-welcome-to-scotland-8742545.html |accessdate=26 October 2016 |date=2013-08-01}}</ref> 432 families own half the private lands in Scotland, and just over 1200 landowners hold 2/3 of Scotland's lands.<ref name=bg07 />\n\nThe [[Crofters' Holdings (Scotland) Act 1886]] intended to protect the farmers' rights, but it was too weak to have any effect.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe Scotland land reform aims to balance the land-ownership situation by:\n* Securing the rights of access to common land,\n* Protecting the rights of tenants and small farmers, and\n* Helping small farmers and communities to buy land from large landowners.\n\n==Devolution and Labour Government (1997\u20132007)==\n{{See also|Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc. (Scotland) Act 2000|Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003}}\nIn 1997 a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Blair ministry|Government]] was elected to Westminster on a manifesto which included both devolution and land reform. Upon election, a Land Reform Policy Group (LRPG) was established under the chairmanship of [[Lord Sewel]], then [[Scottish Office]] Minister of State, who was also tasked with steering devolution legislation though the house of lords. Policy proposals and an extensive public consultation were published by the LRPG in 1999, the same year that the [[1999 Scottish Parliament election|first elections]] to the newly devolved Scottish parliament returned a Labour and Liberal Democrat coalition. Following the momentum of the 1997 and 1999 elections, devolution and the LRPG's proposals, land reform progressed rapidly in the [[1st Scottish Parliament|first session of the Scottish parliament]] with bills introduced to abolish Scotland's feudal land tenure system and a draft land reform bill introduced in 2000. The same year, the [[Scottish Land Fund]] was created and in 2001 began allocating its \u00a310 million budget of national lottery funding to assist rural communities to purchase land.<ref name=bg07 />\n\n=== Abolition of Feudal Tenure ===\nThe first piece of land reform legislation in the 21st century, the [[Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc. (Scotland) Act 2000]] was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 3 May 2000 and received royal assent on 9 June the same year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc. (Scotland) Act 2000 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2000/5/pdfs/asp_20000005_en.pdf |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=1 |language=en |quote=The Bill for this Act of the Scottish Parliament was passed by the Parliament on 3rd May 2000 and received Royal Assent on 9th June 2000.}}</ref> The act formed the core of a three part reform of Scottish property law, alongside the [[Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003]] and [[Tenements (Scotland) Act 2004]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=142 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref> The main provisions of the act included the abolition of feudal superiorities and tenure, to be replaced by a system of outright ownership in which those who had been vassals became outright owners. This necessitated the extinction of superiors\u2019 rights to collect feu duties, for which they were entitled to compensation in the form of a single payment of a size that, when invested at an annual rate of 2.5%, would yield interest equal to the former feu duty.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Guide to the Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc (Scotland) Act 2000 & the Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003 for Housing Associations |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/Doc/17002/0025016.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Executive |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=31 |date=2004 |quote=The formula is set out in section 4 of the 1974 Act \u2013 it requires payment of \u201csuch a sum of money as would, if invested in 2\u00bd per cent. Consolidated Stock at the middle market price at the close of business last preceding the date occurring one month before the said term, produce an annual sum equal to the feuduty\u201d.}}</ref> However, as Scotland's remaining feu duties had been fixed many years previously, inflation meant that by the time of the act's passing their value was, in most cases, effectively nominal.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wightman |first1=Andy |title=The Poor Had No Lawyers |date=2013 |publisher=Birlinn}}</ref> The act also extinguished superiors\u2019 rights to enforce real burdens, conditions on the holding of land, retaining only those conditions enforceable by neighbouring land owners or by certain legal bodies on public policy grounds. The legal basis of real burdens and title conditions was then reformulated in the Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/9/pdfs/asp_20030009_en.pdf |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> The end of feudal tenure simplified titles to land, while the subsequent Title Conditions (Scotland) Act 2003 modernised the types of interests and conditions that can be attached to those titles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=28 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref> Finally, common law surrounding tenements was then reformed in light of these changes under the Tenements (Scotland) Act 2004, completing the abolition of Scotland's feudal property system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |page=142 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n=== The 2003 Acts ===\n2003 saw two important pieces of legislation make their way through the Scottish parliament; the [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003|Land Reform (Scotland) Act]] and the Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act. The Land Reform (Scotland) Act has three parts, with provisions regarding three areas of land rights in Scotland; the creation of a legal framework for [[Freedom to roam|land access]], the community right to buy and crofting community right to buy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/2/pdfs/asp_20030002_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> The first part formalises the tradition in Scotland of unhindered access to open countryside. It creates a framework for responsible access to land and inland water,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/2/notes/division/2 |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 \u2013 Explanatory Notes |publisher=Legislation.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-10-31}}</ref> provided that care was taken not to cause damage or interfere with activities including farming and game stalking. Access rights apply to any non-motorised activities, including walking, cycling, horse-riding and wild camping. They also allow access on inland water for canoeing, rowing, sailing and swimming. This aspect of the Act follows the distinctive approach set out in the [[Scottish Outdoor Access Code]], specifying the rights and responsibilities of land managers, countryside users and recreational managers.<ref>{{cite web |ssrn=1673225 |title=Progressive Property in Action: The Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 by John A. Lovett :: SSRN |publisher=Papers.ssrn.com |date= }}</ref> Similar legislation was passed for [[England]] and [[Wales]] with the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/37/pdfs/ukpga_20000037_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe second part of the act establishes the community right to buy, allowing communities with populations of up to 10,000 to register an interest in land, entitling them to first right of refusal should the owner put the land up for sale or intend to transfer ownership, provided a representative community body can be formed to carry out the purchase.\n\nFinally, the third part establishes the crofting community right to buy which allows crofting communities to purchase crofts and associated land from existing landowners. It differs from the community right to buy in that it can be exercised at any time, regardless of whether the land has been put on the market, allowing crofting communities to purchase land even in the absence of a willing seller.\n\nThe Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act 2003 amends the law relating to agricultural holdings under the Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act 1991. It provides for new forms of agricultural tenancies and makes provision in relation to these tenancies, the right of certain agricultural tenants to buy land and the use of certain agricultural land for non-agricultural purposes. It makes special provision for certain agricultural tenancies where the tenant is a partnership and for the resolution of disputes between landlords and tenants arising under agricultural tenancies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act 2003 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2003/11/pdfs/asp_20030011_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==SNP Government (2007\u2013present)==\n{{See also|Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015|Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016}}\nThe May [[2007 Scottish Parliament election]] resulted, for the first time, in a [[Scottish National Party]] [[minority government]]. The first term of SNP government was marked by a lack of action on land reform. However, following re-election in [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011]], this time with a parliamentary majority, land reform returned to the government agenda with the Scottish Government establishing the '''Land Reform Review Group''' in 2012 and First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] in 2013 announcing a target of seeing 1 million acres of land in community ownership by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=1 million acres short life working group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Environment/land-reform/MillionAcres |website=The Scottish Government |accessdate=26 March 2017}}[[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This content is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/ Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Elliot |first1=Alison |last2=Watt |first2=John |last3=Ian |first3=Cooke |last4=Taylor |first4=Pip |title=The Land of Scotland and the Common Good: Report of the Land Reform Review Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0045/00451087.pdf |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=4 March 2017 |language=English |date=2014}}</ref> The Land Reform Review Group was given the task of identifying how land reform would enable rural and urban communities to have a stake in the ownership, governance, management and use of land, assist in the acquisition and management of that land and promote new relationships between land, people, economy and environment in Scotland. Its final report, published in May 2014, recommended policies to modernise and diversify land ownership in Scotland and encourage sustainable development, some of which would form the basis of the [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015]] and [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016]]. During this period the Land Registration etc. (Scotland) Act 2012 introduced changes to the [[conveyancing]] system in Scotland, with the aim of having all land in Scotland registered under the [[Registers of Scotland|Land Register of Scotland]] within 10 years. Prior to the act, entry of land into the register would be prompted by a sale but other transfers of land would not prompt first entry. The act expanded the triggers for first entry to include any transfer of property or the signing of a long lease in order to accelerate the transition from the antiquated deed based Register of Sassines to the modernised map based Land Register.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gamba |first1=Stephen |title=The Land Registration (Scotland) Act 2012 \u2013 a brief guide |url=http://www.gillespiemacandrew.co.uk/media/321190/gillespie-macandrew-land-reform-scotland-bill-2015-a-brief-guide.pdf |publisher=Gillespie MacAndrew LLP |accessdate=26 March 2017 |date=17 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===The Salvesen v Riddell case (2012\u20132013)===\nIn 2012, a section of the Agricultural Holdings Act was challenged and suspended by the [[Supreme Court of the UK]].<ref name=svr13>{{cite web |title=Salvesen v Riddell and another, Lord Advocate intervening (Scotland) |url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/uksc-2012-0111.html |author=Lord Hope, Lord Kerr, Lord Wilson, Lord Reed, Lord Toulson |publisher=Uk Supreme Court |accessdate=31 October 2016 |date=24 April 2013}}</ref> The trigger for this ruling was an appeal by Salvesen, the owner of Peaston Farm near [[Ormiston]]. The Riddells were tenants in this farm and Section 72 of the 2003 Act greatly restricted the ability of landowners to terminate the tenancies of their tenants. Initially, the start date of this restriction was set to 4 February 2003. This led many landlords, including Salvesen, to terminate the tenancies of their tenants the day before \u2013 3 February 2003. A later amendment to section 72 retroactively set the start date of the restrictions to 16 September 2002, which made Salvesen's termination notice ineffective.\n\nSalvesen applied to the [[Scottish Land Court|Land Court]], which repealed his application. He then appealed to the Court of Session and obtained permission to apply to the UK Supreme Court. His main claim was that Section 72 is incompatible with his property rights, the rights guaranteed to him by [[Article 1 of the European Convention on Human Rights]]. The  Supreme  Court  unanimously  allowed  the  appeal.  It  found  that  Mr.  Salvesen's  A1P1  rights  were  violated  by section  72(10)  of  the  2003  Act  and  that  the  provision  was  outside  the  legislative  competence  of  the  Scottish  Parliament under the [[Scotland Act 1998]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The legal status of unlawful legislation: Salvesen v Riddell [2013] UKSC 22 |url=https://publiclawforeveryone.com/2013/04/25/the-legal-status-of-unlawful-legislation-salvesen-v-riddell-2013-uksc-22/ |date=2013-04-25 |author=Mark Eliott}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The case that keeps surprising \u2013 Salvesen v Riddell |url=http://www.brodies.com/blog/case-keeps-surprising-salvesen-v-riddell/ |accessdate=31 October 2016 |author=Gemma Mckinlay |date=2015-01-29}}</ref>\n\n===Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015===\nThe [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015]], marked the first major piece of land reform legislation to be passed under the SNP government. Its provisions covered different areas pertaining to community empowerment and public participation in policy and planning, including several related directly to land.<ref>{{cite web |title=Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act FAQs |url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/People/engage/CommunityEmpowermentBillFAQs |website=Scottish Government |accessdate=23 March 2017}} [[File:UKOpenGovernmentLicence.svg|30px]] This content is available under the [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/doc/open-government-licence/version/3/ Open Government Licence v3.0]. \u00a9 Crown copyright.</ref> The most important of these was the extension of the Community Right to Buy to communities of any size, including, for the first time, those in urban areas. It also introduced a new community right to buy land which is abandoned, neglected or causing harm to the environmental wellbeing of the community. Similar to the 2003 Act's crofting community right to buy, this new right does not require a willing seller. Rather, Scottish ministers may compel a landowner to sell to communities with a registered interest, if they deem the sale likely to contribute to sustainable local development.\n\nFurther provisions granted community bodies the right to request to purchase, lease, manage or use land and buildings held by local authorities, Scottish ministers and other Scottish public bodies, of which relevant authorities are required to create and maintain a publicly available register. The Act reformed [[Common Good Fund|Common Good Property]], requiring local authorities to establish and maintain registers of all common good property held by them and to inform and consult local community bodies before any change of use or disposal of common good property. Allotments, updates and simplifies legislation on allotments.\n\nIt also set a requirement for local authorities to take steps to provide [[Allotment (gardening)|allotments]] should waiting lists exceed certain lengths and strengthened protections for allotments, regulated rents and allowed tenants to sell food produced on allotments on a not for profit basis. The act required that local authorities develop food growing strategies, including the identification of land that may be used as allotment sites or potential land for community cultivation.\n\nIt has been found that the Scottish approach to [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015|community empowerment and localism]] marks an example of policy divergence from the rest of the UK<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rolfe |first1=Steve |title=Divergence in Community Participation Policy: Analysing Localism and Community Empowerment Using a Theory of Change Approach |journal=Local Government Studies |volume=42 |pages=97\u2013118 |doi=10.1080/03003930.2015.1081848 |year=2016 |hdl=1893/23241 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> but that significant challenges remain in how to ensure a shared strategy; shared resources; and shared accountability.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Elliott |first1=Ian |last2=Fejszes |first2=Violetta |last3=T\u00e0rrega |first3=Mariola |title=The Community Empowerment Act and localism under devolution in Scotland: The perspective of multiple stakeholders in a council ward |journal=International Journal of Public Sector Management |doi=10.1108/IJPSM-03-2018-0080 |year=2018 |url=http://nrl.northumbria.ac.uk/36095/1/Elliott%20et%20al%20-%20The%20Community%20Empowerment%20Act%20and%20Localism%20under%20Devolution%20in%20Scotland%20AAM.pdf }}</ref>\n\n===Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016===\nIn 2013 [[Richard Lochhead]], then [[Cabinet Secretary for the Rural Economy and Connectivity|Cabinet Secretary for Rural Affairs and the Environment]], announced the launch of the Agricultural Holdings Review, which would examine the situation of land ownership and use, tenant-owner relationships, and all of the relevant legislation. The Review published its final report in January 2015, and the recommendations were put out to consultation.\n<ref name=\"review\">{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date=January 2015 |title=Review of Agricultural Holdings Legislation Final Report |url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0046/00468852.pdf |publisher=Scottish Government |format=PDF |location=Edinburgh |access-date=25 April 2017 |quote=&nbsp;}}</ref><ref name=\"consultation\">{{cite web |last1=Land Reform Team |title=A Consultation on the future of Land Reform in Scotland |url=https://consult.scotland.gov.uk/land-reform-and-tenancy-unit/land-reform-scotland |year=2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the responses to the consultation the [[Scottish Government]] presented the ''Land Reform (Scotland) Bill'' to the [[Scottish Parliament]] on 22 June 2015. The Bill was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 16 March 2016, and received Royal Assent on 22 March 2016 becoming [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016]].<ref name=\"bill-parliament\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/Bills/90675.aspx |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Bill |date=18 June 2015 |website=www.parliament.scot |access-date=25 April 2017}}</ref> The most radical and controversial provision of the act was the creation of the Community Right to Buy for Sustainable Development. This permitted [[Scottish Ministers]] to approve the purchase of privately owned land by a community body with a registered interest. Like the Crofting Community Right to Buy and the Community Right to Buy abandoned or derelict land, the Community Right to Buy for Sustainable Development does not require a willing seller but allows ministers to compel landowners to sell if they decide that the sale will further sustainable development in the area.<ref>{{cite web |title=Community rights to buy in Scotland \u2013 which is which, and what are they for? |url=http://www.brodies.com/node/8185 |website=Brodies |accessdate=5 March 2017 |language=en}}</ref> Community bodies may also register an interest in allowing a third party to purchase land on the same basis.\n\nThis new Community Right to Buy was not the only provision of the Act. The Act required that the Scottish Government produce a 'Land Rights and Responsibilities Statement', setting out its objectives for land reform and to establish a [[Scottish Land Commission]] to take forward the land reform process and prepare a strategic plan, for the approval of [[Scottish Ministers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blair |first1=Mike |title=A Brief Guide to Land Reform in Scotland |url=http://www.gillespiemacandrew.co.uk/media/340813/land-reform-act-2016.pdf |publisher=Gillespie Macandrew LLP |accessdate=5 March 2017 |date=April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306131212/http://www.gillespiemacandrew.co.uk/media/340813/land-reform-act-2016.pdf |archive-date=6 March 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other provisions of the act included new regulations to require persons who control land to be identified, with information obtained to appear in the Land Register of Scotland; the removal of sporting rights exemption from rates, are to be re-valued; and further powers for [[Scottish Natural Heritage]] to control deer management. It also makes provision for notice and consultation where core paths are to be amended.<ref>{{cite web |title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2016/18/pdfs/asp_20160018_en.pdf |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nFurther provisions of the Act pertain to agricultural tenancies including new protections for tenant farmers against eviction, the introduction of a modernised limited duration tenancy with greater rights for tenants relative to landowners and the widening of eligible assignees and inheritors of tenancies. Additionally, tenants under the 1991 Agricultural Holdings (Scotland) Act are now presumed to have registered their right to buy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scottish farmer facing eviction wins last-minute reprieve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/nov/26/scottish-farmer-facing-eviction-wins-last-minute-reprieve |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=guardian16>{{cite web |title=A new dawn for land reform in Scotland? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/scotland-blog/2016/mar/17/a-new-dawn-for-land-reform-in-scotland |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Holyrood approves sweeping Scottish land reforms |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3b4234da-eb55-11e5-bb79-2303682345c8 |accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n=== Criticism by landlords ===\nIn August 2013, landowners including the [[Duke of Roxburghe]] expressed concerns about the work of the Land Reform Review Group and the focus on community ownership. The landowners stated that private ownership brought efficiency and greater protection for [[endangered species]] from development of land. Also, there were other social, economic, and environmental benefits to private ownership of Scottish land. The Duke of Roxburghe raised concerns specifically about the economic impacts, and the impact on the agricultural sector, saying:\n{{Quote|Radical proposals that threaten private property rights and which impact adversely on private enterprise, investment and development or which deprive young aspiring farmers the opportunity to get a firm foothold on the farming ladder would be immensely damaging in our view and act against the interests of the communities involved.|Duke of Roxburghe|August 2013, quoted in ''[[The Scotsman]]'' newspaper|<ref name=\"scotsman-2013-august\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/lairds-warn-holyrood-over-new-land-buy-out-powers-1-3023862 |title=Lairds warn Holyrood over new land buy-out powers |website=www.scotsman.com |language=en |date=1 August 2013 |access-date=27 April 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nMany other landlords opposed the passage of the Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2016. Mark Coombs, the estate manager of the {{convert|33,000|ha|acre|abbr=on}} Queensberry Estate, owned by the [[Duke of Buccleuch|10th Duke of Buccleuch]], stated that \"there are also concerns if the purpose of changing the ownership is simply to allow another party \u2026 to carry out the same activity as is currently being undertaken by the existing owner as this strikes at the essence of ownership rights and suggests a clear move towards a more collectivist political view which is not representative of the body politic of Scotland.\" Thus hurting the property rights of the landowners since it strips them of control of their property.<ref name=independent13 />\n\nDavid Johnstone, chairman of Scottish Land and Estates, said the proposal could lead to land not being made available to let, and hurting the tenant farming sector. Johnstone said: \"What you are doing is giving a tenant a stake in the capital value of the farm. If the landlord doesn\u2019t have the ability to pay, then the farm never comes back... That has got to have a knock on effect in the confidence of anyone who might wish to come to let land or is letting land at the moment.\"<ref name=telegraph15>{{cite news |last1=Auslan Cramb |title=Property rights threatened by 'aggressive' change in land reform bill |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/earth/countryside/12057440/Property-rights-threatened-by-aggressive-change-in-land-reform-bill.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=31 October 2016 |date=2015-12-18}}</ref>\n\nSeafield and Strathspey Estates argued that land concentration is not a bad thing, as it may lead to more efficient management. Seafield and Strathspey Estates is a {{convert|35,000|ha|acre|abbr=on}} enterprise which includes salmon beats on the [[River Spey]], and is managed on behalf of the family of the [[Earl of Seafield]]. It said landowners were being blamed for the inefficiencies of local and central government. \"There is a myth presented by individuals sponsoring land reform in Scotland that 'too many acres are owned by too few individuals.' It may be true that 'many acres are owned by few individuals' but there is very little evidence presented to show that this is a bad thing\".<ref name=independent13 />\n\n=== Criticism by Scottish Parliament ===\nThe Land Reform (Scotland) Bill was criticised during its passage by the [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|Delegated Powers and Law Reform Committee]] of the Scottish Parliament on the basis that it granted a significant power to [[Scottish Ministers|Scottish Minister]] to implement much of the details of the Act through [[Scottish Statutory Instrument|secondary legislation]] and delegated powers. Turcan Connell identified concerns around the implementation of the Act and the amount of scrutiny the detailed law would receive.<ref name=\"turcan-connell\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.turcanconnell.com/media/constitutional-issues/scottish-land-reform/articles/2016/04/land-reform-update-april-2016/ |title=Land Reform Update \u2013 April 2016 |date=27 April 2016 |website=Turcan Connell |publisher=Turcan Connell |language=en |access-date=25 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426055558/https://www.turcanconnell.com/media/constitutional-issues/scottish-land-reform/articles/2016/04/land-reform-update-april-2016/ |archive-date=26 April 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Recommendations by legal experts ===\nSeveral parts of the Bill have been criticized as follows:<ref name=ms15>{{cite journal |doi=10.2139/ssrn.2698578 |title=The Land Reform (Scotland) Bill and Human Rights: Key Points and Recommendations |year=2015 |last1=MacInnes |first1=Megan |last2=Shields |first2=Kirsteen}}</ref>\n* The criteria for community buyout (s.47) is too demanding. There are double criteria: significant benefit from the transfer, and significant harm from non-transfer. Each one of these criteria alone should be sufficient.\n* The upper bound of 10 years on tenancy (part 10, s.74) is too short and hurts the rights of the tenants.\n* The paragraphs on transparency and accountability (parts 3-4, s.35-36) are too weak: there are no sanctions on refusing to give information about the landowner, and there is no obligation to give information on the real person owning the land (the real landowner often hides behind a \"shell company\").\n\nLand-reform activists claim that the current reform is insufficient as several important amendments were voted down by SNP and Conservative backbenchers, including:<ref name=guardian16 />\n* Land cap \u2013 restricting the amount of land that one individual can own.\n* Preventing land ownership via offshore tax havens. Andy Wightman, the land reform spokesperson for the Scottish Greens and MSP candidate for Lothian, revealed that companies owned by the Buccleuch Estates used tax havens in the Cayman Islands. He said that \"The Green bid to clamp down on the use of tax havens goes to the heart of understanding who owns Scotland. As we have seen this week with the uncovering of the complex corporate affairs of the Buccleuch Estates, there is an urgent need to ensure transparency in who profits from Scottish land.\"\n\n=== Criticism by PhD students ===\nIn a 2016 article in the journal of the [[Law Society of Scotland]], Douglas Maxwell claims the Land Reform (Scotland) Bill contains poorly-defined terms such as \"sustainable development\" and \"communities\" which may place the bill in conflict with international human rights laws, particularly the [[ECHR]] [[Protocol 1, article 1]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Douglas Maxwell |title=Human rights and land reform: unanswered questions |url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/Magazine/61-1/1021198.aspx |date=2016-01-18}}</ref>\n\n== Community focus ==\nLand reform in Scotland is unusual in its emphasis on [[community ownership|community land ownership]], with the Scottish government adopting the target of seeing 1 million acres of land under community ownership by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=One Million Acres by 2020 \u2013 Strategy report and recommendations from the 1 Million Acre Short Life Working Group |url=http://www.gov.scot/Publications/2015/12/5735 |publisher=The Scottish Government |accessdate=6 March 2017 |date=2015}}</ref><ref name=bg07>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2005.09.004 |title=Community-based land reform: Lessons from Scotland |journal=Land Use Policy |volume=24 |pages=24\u201334 |year=2007 |last1=Bryden |first1=John |last2=Geisler |first2=Charles}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2012.07.013 |title=Why community ownership? Understanding land reform in Scotland |journal=Land Use Policy |volume=31 |pages=289\u2013297 |year=2013 |last1=Hoffman |first1=Matthew}}</ref> Most other land reforms have focused on giving land ownership rights to individual farmers. In contrast, the Land Reform (Scotland) Acts of 2003 and 2016 grant a collective right-to-buy to entire communities living in a geographical area.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Scottish Land Court]]\n* [[Lands Tribunal for Scotland]]\n* [[Registers of Scotland]]\n* [[Scottish Land Restoration League]]\n* [[Highland Land League]]\n* [[Scottish Land Fund]]\n* [[List of community buyouts in Scotland]]\n* [[Right of public access to the wilderness]]\n* [[Community ownership]]\n* [[Community Land Scotland]]\n* [[Land raid]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gov.scot/Topics/farmingrural/Rural/rural-land Rural land] on Scottish Government website\n* [http://www.outdooraccess-scotland.com/the-act-and-the-code/introduction Scottish Outdoor Access Code] on www.outdooraccess-scotland.com\n* [http://www.mcofs.org.uk/know-the-code.asp The Mountaineering Council of Scotland \u2014 Know the Code]\n* {{UK-LEG|path=asp/2003/2|title=Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003|type=asp}}\n\n{{Sustainable development in Scotland}}\n{{Jacobitism}}\n{{UK legislation}}\n\n[[Category:Land reform in Scotland| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dl\u00edod\u00f3ir95", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Salvesen v Riddell case (2012\u20132013):Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_reform_in_Scotland"}
{"title_page": "Jack Harlow", "text_new": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jack Harlow\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jackman Thomas Harlow<ref>[https://repertoire.bmi.com/Catalog.aspx?detail=writerid&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&keyid=1977162&subid=0] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1998|03|13}}\n| birth_place      = [[Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|Generation Now|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|Private Garden|[[Cyhi the Prynce]]|[[Don Cannon]]|[[Bryson Tiller]]|[[DJ Drama]]|2forwOyNE|Shloob|Ace Pro|Ronnie Lucciano|Quiiso}}\n| website          = {{URL|jackharlow.us/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jackman Thomas \"Jack\" Harlow''' (born March 13, 1998)<ref name=\"LouisMain\">{{cite news | last=Moss| first=Josh| title =Kid with a Mic| work =Louisville| date =4 August 2017 | url =https://www.louisville.com/content/kid-mic| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> is an American rapper and songwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/02/05/jack-harlow-stays-true-to-his-roots|title=Jack Harlow Stays True to His Roots|work=The Fader|date=February 5, 2019|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> He is signed to Generation Now and [[Atlantic Records]]. He is also the co-founder of his own musical collective, Private Garden. He is best known for his single \"[[Whats Poppin]]\", which peaked at number 36 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]].\n\n==Early life==\nHarlow was born and raised in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"XXLBreak\">{{cite news | last=Krastz| first=Roger| title =The Break Presents: Jack Harlow| publisher =XXL| date =12 January 2018 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/01/jack-harlow-interview-the-break/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"BBOct\">{{cite news | last=Elibert| first=Mark| title =Jack Harlow Talks 'Loose' Mixtape, Putting Louisville on the Map & Working With DJ Drama, Don Cannon| publisher =Billboard| date =10 October 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8478971/jack-harlow-loose-mixtape-dj-drama-interview| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> Harlow began rapping at age 12. He and a friend used a ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' microphone and a laptop to record rhymes and songs. They made a [[Compact disc|CD]] entitled ''Rippin' and Rappin{{'}}'' and sold copies at their school ([[Highland Middle School (Louisville, Kentucky)|Highland Middle School]]). When he was in seventh grade, Harlow acquired a professional microphone and made his first mixtape, ''Extra Credit'', using the moniker \"Mr. Harlow\".<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/>\n\nHarlow attended [[Atherton High School]], graduating in 2016. During his freshman year, his [[YouTube]] videos drew the attention of major labels, but he chose not to pursue any of the deals offered to him at the time. In November 2014 during his junior year, he released another mixtape, ''Finally Handsome''.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"DJBFinally\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Jack Harlow - Finally Handsome | publisher=DJ Booth| date =7 November 2014 | url =https://djbooth.net/index/albums/review/jack-harlow-finally-handsome| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117025429/https://djbooth.net/index/albums/review/jack-harlow-finally-handsome| archive-date=17 January 2015| url-status=dead| access-date =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn November 2015, Harlow released his first commercial album, an [[Extended play|EP]] entitled ''The Handsome Harlow''. It was released through [[Gill Holland]]'s sonaBLAST! record label.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"Louis2\">{{cite news | last=Messmer| first=Alexis| title =Jack Harlow Talks His First Commercial Release and What's Next | publisher =Louisville| date =18 December 2015 | url =https://www.louisville.com/content/jack-harlow-talks-his-first-commercial-release-and-whats-next| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> Throughout high school, he often played sold out shows at Louisville venues like the [[Mercury Ballroom]], Headliners, and the Haymarket Whiskey Bar.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"XXLBreak\"/> In early 2016, he released a single, \"Never Woulda Known\", which featured Johnny Spanish and was produced by Syk Sense. In March of that year, he opened for [[Vince Staples]] in Louisville.<ref name=\"CJ\">{{cite news | last=Puckett| first=Jeffrey Lee| title =Rapper Jack Harlow is on it like MacGyver| newspaper =The Courier-Journal| date =8 March 2016 | url =https://www.courier-journal.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/03/08/jack-harlow-louisville-rapper/81228018/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016 less than a month after graduating high school, he released the mixtape, ''18'', which was the first album on his label and music collective, Private Garden.<ref name=\"EMIntro\">{{cite news | last=Luisa| first=Paige| title =Introducing: Jack Harlow| publisher =Ear Milk| date =18 July 2016 | url =https://earmilk.com/2016/07/18/introducing-jack-harlow/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LEO18\">{{cite news | last=Bishop| first=Syd| title =Into the wild: A conversation with Jack Harlow| newspaper =Louisville Eccentric Observer| date =15 June 2016 | url =https://www.leoweekly.com/2016/06/wild-conversation-jack-harlow/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The collective also features Harlow's frequent collaborators, the Homies, composed of Louisville rappers and producers Ace Pro, 2forwOyNE, Shloob, Quiiso, and Ronnie Lucciano.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/> Over the course of the next year, Harlow performed at [[South by Southwest]], [[Bonnaroo Music Festival|Bonnaroo]], and the [[Forecastle Festival]]. He also spent time traveling back and forth between Louisville and [[Atlanta]] to work with engineer/mixer, KY Engineering. In March 2017, he released the song \"Hitchcock\", produced by 2forwOyNE and J-Reid.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"Weiss\">{{cite news | last=Poe| first=Allen| title =North By Northwest: On Jack Harlow's \"Hitchcock\"| publisher =Passion of the Weiss| date =13 March 2017 | url =https://www.passionweiss.com/2017/03/13/jack-harlow-hitchcock/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2017, he released the single \"Routine\".<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/> In October of that year, he released another single, \"Dark Knight\", with an accompanying music video. He credits [[Cyhi the Prynce|CyHi the Prynce]] with helping him work through his [[writer's block]] and finish the song.<ref name=\"MA\">{{cite news | last=Lakshminarayana| first=Raghava| title =PREMIERE: Jack Harlow \"Dark Knight\"| publisher =Mass Appeal| date =27 October 2017 | url =http://archive.massappeal.com/jack-harlow-dark-night-premiere/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sub\">{{cite news | last=Shotwell| first=James| title =Jack Harlow's impending superstardom cannot be denied on \"Dark Knight\"| website =Substream| date =28 October 2017 | url =https://substreammagazine.com/2017/10/jack-harlow-dark-knight/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The song would become the lead single off Harlow's mixtape ''Gazebo'', which was released in November 2017.<ref name=\"XXLBreak\"/> He went on a 14-city Gazebo Tour in support of the album. The Homies opened for Harlow, and the tour ended in January 2018.<ref name=\"LEOGaz\">{{cite news | last=Bishop| first=Syd| title =Jack Harlow talks about the songs on 'Gazebo'| newspaper =Louisville Eccentric Observer| date =24 January 2018 | url =https://www.leoweekly.com/2018/01/jack-harlow-talks/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ISD\">{{cite news | last=Babcock| first=Trevor| title =Review: Jack Harlow makes a bold debut at the M-Shop| newspaper =Iowa State Daily| date =23 January 2018 | url =http://www.iowastatedaily.com/ames247/review-jack-harlow-makes-a-bold-debut-at-the-m/article_82206da8-00cb-11e8-a15d-5b165007912e.html| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, Harlow opened for indie rock band, [[Portugal. The Man]] on select tour dates.<ref name=\"Live\">{{cite news | last=Newcomb| first=Ming Lee| title =Portugal. The Man Announces New Tour Dates For 2018| publisher =Live for Live Music| date =6 February 2018 | url =https://liveforlivemusic.com/news/portugal-man-2018-new/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news | last=Tady| first=Scott| title =Portugal. The Man did it their way in Pittsburgh| newspaper =The Beaver County Times| date =23 May 2018 | url =http://www.timesonline.com/entertainmentlife/20180523/portugal-man-did-it-their-way-in-pittsburgh| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The following month, he was featured alongside [[Lil James]] and Sixteen on the [[Skeme]] song \"Get Sumn\".<ref name=\"YC\">{{cite news | last=Garner| first=Matthew| title =Skeme \"Get Sumn\" feat. Jack Harlow, Sixteen & Lil James| publisher =Young California| date =11 June 2018 | url =http://www.youngcalifornia.com/2018/06/skeme-get-sumn-feat-jack-harlow-sixteen-lil-james/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, it was announced that Harlow had signed to [[DJ Drama]] and [[Don Cannon]]'s [[Atlantic Records]] imprint, Generation Now. He also released a video for his single \"Sundown\" on the day of the announcement.<ref name=\"BBAug\">{{cite news | last=Saponara| first=Michael| title =Jack Harlow Signs With Generation Now & Atlantic Records, Premieres Frenetic 'SUNDOWN' Video: Exclusive| publisher =Billboard| date =3 August 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8468418/jack-harlow-signs-with-atlantic-records-generation-now-sundown-video| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"XXLGN\">{{cite news | last=Seabrook III| first=Robby| title =Jack Harlow Signs With Generation Now and Atlantic Records| publisher =XXL| date =3 August 2018 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2018/08/jack-harlow-signs-with-generation-now-atlantic-records/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> On August 17, Harlow released his major label debut mixtape, ''Loose''.<ref name=\"HotNew\">{{cite news | last=A.| first=Aron| title =Jack Harlow Drops New Project \"Loose\" Ft. CyHi The Prynce, K. Camp & More | website =HotNewHipHop| date =17 August 2018 | url =https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jack-harlow-drops-new-project-loose-ft-cyhi-the-prynce-k-camp-and-more-new-mixtape.118343.html| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The album featured guest verses from CyHi the Prynce, [[K Camp]], 2forwOyNE, and Taylor.<ref name=\"XXLLoose\">{{cite news | last=Mojica| first=Nick| title =Jack Harlow \"Loose\" Mixtape: Cyhi The Prynce and K Camp Deliver Guest Verses| publisher =XXL| date =17 August 2018 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2018/08/jack-harlow-loose-mixtape/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, he performed at the [[Genius (website)|Genius]] IQ/BBQ event.<ref name=\"Vibe\">{{cite news | last=Arevalo| first=Lydia| title =2 Chainz To Headline Second Annual Genius IQ/BBQ| publisher =Vibe| date =24 August 2018 | url =https://www.vibe.com/2018/08/2-chainz-to-headline-second-annual-genius-bbq/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> In November 2018, Harlow embarked on a North American tour in support of ''Loose'' that is scheduled to end in late December.<ref name=\"DJB2018\">{{cite news | last=Chesman| first=Donna-Claire| title =How Jack Harlow Became a \"Somebody\" Onstage| publisher =DJ Booth| date =20 November 2018 | url =https://djbooth.net/features/2018-11-20-jack-harlow-became-somebody| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Loyola\">{{cite news | last=Demetrius| first=Alanna| title =Jack Harlow Puts on a Captivating Show at Reggies Rock Club| newspaper =Loyola Phoenix| date =13 November 2018 | url =http://loyolaphoenix.com/2018/11/jack-harlow-puts-on-a-captivating-show-at-reggies-rock-club/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BWW\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Jack Harlow Announces Fall Tour THE LOOSE TOUR| work =Broadway World| date =11 October 2018 | url =https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Jack-Harlow-Announces-Fall-Tour-THE-LOOSE-TOUR-20181011| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> That month, he also released a music video for the song, \"PickYourPhoneUp\", featuring K Camp.<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite news | last=Diaz| first=Angel| title =Premiere: Jack Harlow and K.Camp Want You to \"PICKYOURPHONEUP\" In New Video| work =Complex| date =19 November 2018 | url =https://www.complex.com/music/2018/11/jack-harlow-new-video-premiere-pickyourphoneup-k-camp| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> On August 21, 2019, Harlow released the single \"Thru the Night\" featuring [[Bryson Tiller]] and launched his US tour, which started in October of the same year.\n\nIn January 2020, he released \"[[Whats Poppin]]\", with a music video from video director [[Cole Bennett]], who had also directed videos for artists such as [[Juice Wrld]], [[Lil Tecca]], [[Lil Skies]], and [[Blueface]]. The music video, has surpassed thirty million views as of April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8548634/jack-harlow-whats-poppin-video|title=Jack Harlow Bounces Around the Diner in Cole Bennett-Directed 'Whats Poppin' Video: Watch|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jack-harlow-snaps-on-braggadocios-banger-whats-poppin-new-song.1985876.html|title=Jack Harlow Snaps On Braggadocios Banger \"What's Poppin'\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Jack Harlow - WHATS POPPIN (Dir. by @_ColeBennett_)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w9uWPBDHEKE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> On his most recent birthday, March 13, 2020, he released a seven-track project called ''Sweet Action''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jack-harlow-ep-sweet-action|title=Listen to Jack Harlow's EP 'Sweet Action'|work=Complex|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of mixtapes with selected album details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Finally Handsome''\n|\n* Released: November 7, 2014\n* Label: [[Independent music|Self-released]]\n* Formats: [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''18''\n|\n* Released: June 17, 2016\n* Label: Self-released\n* Formats: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Gazebo''\n|\n* Released: November 17, 2017\n* Label: Self-released\n* Formats: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Loose''\n|\n* Released: August 17, 2018\n* Label: Generation Now, [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* Formats: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Confetti''\n|\n* Released: September 20, 2019\n* Label: Generation Now, Atlantic\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of extended plays with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Jack+Harlow&chartcode=TLP|title=Chart Search: Jack Harlow, Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2020/03/23/charts-march-22-2020|title=On The Charts: March 22, 2020|website=FYIMusicNews|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Handsome Harlow''\n|\n* Released: November 13, 2015\n* Label: sonaBLAST!\n* Format: Digital download\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Sweet Action''\n|\n* Released: March 13, 2020\n* Label: Generation Now, Atlantic\n* Format: Digital download, streaming\n| 36 || 32\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! colspan=\"9\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Jack+Harlow&chartcode=HSI|title=Chart Search: Jack Harlow, Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br/>(FL)<br/>Tip]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jack+Harlow|title=Discografie Jack Harlow|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Hot 100|CAN]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Jack+Harlow&chartcode=CAN|title=Chart Search: Jack Harlow, Billboard Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/irish-singles-chart/20200417/ie7501|title=Official Irish Singles Chart Top 50|publisher=Official Charts Company|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=4845|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/41?dspy=2020&dspp=16|title=Veckolista Singlar, vecka 16|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jack+Harlow|title=Discographie Jack Harlow|website=hitparade.ch|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/57428/jack-harlow/|title=Jack Harlow {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Never Woulda Known\"<br /><small>(featuring Johnny Spanish)</small>\n| 2016\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''18''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Hitchcock\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2017\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Gazebo''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Routine\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Dark Knight\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Sundown\"\n| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''Loose''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Thru the Night\"<br />{{small|(featuring [[Bryson Tiller]])}}\n| 2019\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''Confetti''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Whats Poppin]]\"\n| 2020\n| 36 || 35 || 24 || 30 || 26 || 32 || 66 || 85 || 47\n| ''Sweet Action''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harlow, Jack}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jack Harlow\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jackman Thomas Harlow<ref>[https://repertoire.bmi.com/Catalog.aspx?detail=writerid&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&keyid=1977162&subid=0] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1998|03|13}}\n| birth_place      = [[Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|Generation Now|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|Private Garden|[[Cyhi the Prynce]]|[[Don Cannon]]|[[Bryson Tiller]]|[[DJ Drama]]|2forwOyNE|Shloob|Ace Pro|Ronnie Lucciano|Quiiso}}\n| website          = {{URL|jackharlow.us/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jackman Thomas \"Jack\" Harlow''' (born March 13, 1998)<ref name=\"LouisMain\">{{cite news | last=Moss| first=Josh| title =Kid with a Mic| work =Louisville| date =4 August 2017 | url =https://www.louisville.com/content/kid-mic| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> is an American rapper and songwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/02/05/jack-harlow-stays-true-to-his-roots|title=Jack Harlow Stays True to His Roots|work=The Fader|date=February 5, 2019|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> He is signed to Generation Now and [[Atlantic Records]]. He is also the co-founder of his own musical collective, Private Garden. He is best known for his single \"[[Whats Poppin]]\", which peaked at number 36 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]].\n\n==Early life==\nHarlow was born and raised in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"XXLBreak\">{{cite news | last=Krastz| first=Roger| title =The Break Presents: Jack Harlow| publisher =XXL| date =12 January 2018 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/01/jack-harlow-interview-the-break/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"BBOct\">{{cite news | last=Elibert| first=Mark| title =Jack Harlow Talks 'Loose' Mixtape, Putting Louisville on the Map & Working With DJ Drama, Don Cannon| publisher =Billboard| date =10 October 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8478971/jack-harlow-loose-mixtape-dj-drama-interview| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> Harlow began rapping at age 12. He and a friend used a ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' microphone and a laptop to record rhymes and songs. They made a [[Compact disc|CD]] entitled ''Rippin' and Rappin{{'}}'' and sold copies at their school ([[Highland Middle School (Louisville, Kentucky)|Highland Middle School]]). When he was in seventh grade, Harlow acquired a professional microphone and made his first mixtape, ''Extra Credit'', using the moniker \"Mr. Harlow\".<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/>\n\nHarlow attended [[Atherton High School]], graduating in 2016. During his freshman year, his [[YouTube]] videos drew the attention of major labels, but he chose not to pursue any of the deals offered to him at the time. In November 2014 during his junior year, he released another mixtape, ''Finally Handsome''.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"DJBFinally\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Jack Harlow - Finally Handsome | publisher=DJ Booth| date =7 November 2014 | url =https://djbooth.net/index/albums/review/jack-harlow-finally-handsome| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117025429/https://djbooth.net/index/albums/review/jack-harlow-finally-handsome| archive-date=17 January 2015| url-status=dead| access-date =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn November 2015, Harlow released his first commercial album, an [[Extended play|EP]] entitled ''The Handsome Harlow''. It was released through [[Gill Holland]]'s sonaBLAST! record label.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"Louis2\">{{cite news | last=Messmer| first=Alexis| title =Jack Harlow Talks His First Commercial Release and What's Next | publisher =Louisville| date =18 December 2015 | url =https://www.louisville.com/content/jack-harlow-talks-his-first-commercial-release-and-whats-next| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> Throughout high school, he often played sold out shows at Louisville venues like the [[Mercury Ballroom]], Headliners, and the Haymarket Whiskey Bar.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"XXLBreak\"/> In early 2016, he released a single, \"Never Woulda Known\", which featured Johnny Spanish and was produced by Syk Sense. In March of that year, he opened for [[Vince Staples]] in Louisville.<ref name=\"CJ\">{{cite news | last=Puckett| first=Jeffrey Lee| title =Rapper Jack Harlow is on it like MacGyver| newspaper =The Courier-Journal| date =8 March 2016 | url =https://www.courier-journal.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/03/08/jack-harlow-louisville-rapper/81228018/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016 less than a month after graduating high school, he released the mixtape, ''18'', which was the first album on his label and music collective, Private Garden.<ref name=\"EMIntro\">{{cite news | last=Luisa| first=Paige| title =Introducing: Jack Harlow| publisher =Ear Milk| date =18 July 2016 | url =https://earmilk.com/2016/07/18/introducing-jack-harlow/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LEO18\">{{cite news | last=Bishop| first=Syd| title =Into the wild: A conversation with Jack Harlow| newspaper =Louisville Eccentric Observer| date =15 June 2016 | url =https://www.leoweekly.com/2016/06/wild-conversation-jack-harlow/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The collective also features Harlow's frequent collaborators, the Homies, composed of Louisville rappers and producers Ace Pro, 2forwOyNE, Shloob, Quiiso, and Ronnie Lucciano.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/> Over the course of the next year, Harlow performed at [[South by Southwest]], [[Bonnaroo Music Festival|Bonnaroo]], and the [[Forecastle Festival]]. He also spent time traveling back and forth between Louisville and [[Atlanta]] to work with engineer/mixer, KY Engineering. In March 2017, he released the song \"Hitchcock\", produced by 2forwOyNE and J-Reid.<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/><ref name=\"Weiss\">{{cite news | last=Poe| first=Allen| title =North By Northwest: On Jack Harlow's \"Hitchcock\"| publisher =Passion of the Weiss| date =13 March 2017 | url =https://www.passionweiss.com/2017/03/13/jack-harlow-hitchcock/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2017, he released the single \"Routine\".<ref name=\"LouisMain\"/> In October of that year, he released another single, \"Dark Knight\", with an accompanying music video. He credits [[Cyhi the Prynce|CyHi the Prynce]] with helping him work through his [[writer's block]] and finish the song.<ref name=\"MA\">{{cite news | last=Lakshminarayana| first=Raghava| title =PREMIERE: Jack Harlow \"Dark Knight\"| publisher =Mass Appeal| date =27 October 2017 | url =http://archive.massappeal.com/jack-harlow-dark-night-premiere/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sub\">{{cite news | last=Shotwell| first=James| title =Jack Harlow's impending superstardom cannot be denied on \"Dark Knight\"| website =Substream| date =28 October 2017 | url =https://substreammagazine.com/2017/10/jack-harlow-dark-knight/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The song would become the lead single off Harlow's mixtape ''Gazebo'', which was released in November 2017.<ref name=\"XXLBreak\"/> He went on a 14-city Gazebo Tour in support of the album. The Homies opened for Harlow, and the tour ended in January 2018.<ref name=\"LEOGaz\">{{cite news | last=Bishop| first=Syd| title =Jack Harlow talks about the songs on 'Gazebo'| newspaper =Louisville Eccentric Observer| date =24 January 2018 | url =https://www.leoweekly.com/2018/01/jack-harlow-talks/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ISD\">{{cite news | last=Babcock| first=Trevor| title =Review: Jack Harlow makes a bold debut at the M-Shop| newspaper =Iowa State Daily| date =23 January 2018 | url =http://www.iowastatedaily.com/ames247/review-jack-harlow-makes-a-bold-debut-at-the-m/article_82206da8-00cb-11e8-a15d-5b165007912e.html| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, Harlow opened for indie rock band, [[Portugal. The Man]] on select tour dates.<ref name=\"Live\">{{cite news | last=Newcomb| first=Ming Lee| title =Portugal. The Man Announces New Tour Dates For 2018| publisher =Live for Live Music| date =6 February 2018 | url =https://liveforlivemusic.com/news/portugal-man-2018-new/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news | last=Tady| first=Scott| title =Portugal. The Man did it their way in Pittsburgh| newspaper =The Beaver County Times| date =23 May 2018 | url =http://www.timesonline.com/entertainmentlife/20180523/portugal-man-did-it-their-way-in-pittsburgh| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The following month, he was featured alongside [[Lil James]] and Sixteen on the [[Skeme]] song \"Get Sumn\".<ref name=\"YC\">{{cite news | last=Garner| first=Matthew| title =Skeme \"Get Sumn\" feat. Jack Harlow, Sixteen & Lil James| publisher =Young California| date =11 June 2018 | url =http://www.youngcalifornia.com/2018/06/skeme-get-sumn-feat-jack-harlow-sixteen-lil-james/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, it was announced that Harlow had signed to [[DJ Drama]] and [[Don Cannon]]'s [[Atlantic Records]] imprint, Generation Now. He also released a video for his single \"Sundown\" on the day of the announcement.<ref name=\"BBAug\">{{cite news | last=Saponara| first=Michael| title =Jack Harlow Signs With Generation Now & Atlantic Records, Premieres Frenetic 'SUNDOWN' Video: Exclusive| publisher =Billboard| date =3 August 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8468418/jack-harlow-signs-with-atlantic-records-generation-now-sundown-video| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"XXLGN\">{{cite news | last=Seabrook III| first=Robby| title =Jack Harlow Signs With Generation Now and Atlantic Records| publisher =XXL| date =3 August 2018 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2018/08/jack-harlow-signs-with-generation-now-atlantic-records/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> On August 17, Harlow released his major label debut mixtape, ''Loose''.<ref name=\"HotNew\">{{cite news | last=A.| first=Aron| title =Jack Harlow Drops New Project \"Loose\" Ft. CyHi The Prynce, K. Camp & More | website =HotNewHipHop| date =17 August 2018 | url =https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jack-harlow-drops-new-project-loose-ft-cyhi-the-prynce-k-camp-and-more-new-mixtape.118343.html| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> The album featured guest verses from CyHi the Prynce, [[K Camp]], 2forwOyNE, and Taylor.<ref name=\"XXLLoose\">{{cite news | last=Mojica| first=Nick| title =Jack Harlow \"Loose\" Mixtape: Cyhi The Prynce and K Camp Deliver Guest Verses| publisher =XXL| date =17 August 2018 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2018/08/jack-harlow-loose-mixtape/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, he performed at the [[Genius (website)|Genius]] IQ/BBQ event.<ref name=\"Vibe\">{{cite news | last=Arevalo| first=Lydia| title =2 Chainz To Headline Second Annual Genius IQ/BBQ| publisher =Vibe| date =24 August 2018 | url =https://www.vibe.com/2018/08/2-chainz-to-headline-second-annual-genius-bbq/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> In November 2018, Harlow embarked on a North American tour in support of ''Loose'' that is scheduled to end in late December.<ref name=\"DJB2018\">{{cite news | last=Chesman| first=Donna-Claire| title =How Jack Harlow Became a \"Somebody\" Onstage| publisher =DJ Booth| date =20 November 2018 | url =https://djbooth.net/features/2018-11-20-jack-harlow-became-somebody| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Loyola\">{{cite news | last=Demetrius| first=Alanna| title =Jack Harlow Puts on a Captivating Show at Reggies Rock Club| newspaper =Loyola Phoenix| date =13 November 2018 | url =http://loyolaphoenix.com/2018/11/jack-harlow-puts-on-a-captivating-show-at-reggies-rock-club/| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BWW\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Jack Harlow Announces Fall Tour THE LOOSE TOUR| work =Broadway World| date =11 October 2018 | url =https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Jack-Harlow-Announces-Fall-Tour-THE-LOOSE-TOUR-20181011| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> That month, he also released a music video for the song, \"PickYourPhoneUp\", featuring K Camp.<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite news | last=Diaz| first=Angel| title =Premiere: Jack Harlow and K.Camp Want You to \"PICKYOURPHONEUP\" In New Video| work =Complex| date =19 November 2018 | url =https://www.complex.com/music/2018/11/jack-harlow-new-video-premiere-pickyourphoneup-k-camp| accessdate =13 December 2018}}</ref> On August 21, 2019, Harlow released the single \"Thru the Night\" featuring [[Bryson Tiller]] and launched his US tour, which started in October of the same year.\n\nIn January 2020, he released \"[[Whats Poppin]]\", with a music video from video director [[Cole Bennett]], who had also directed videos for artists such as [[Juice Wrld]], [[Lil Tecca]], [[Lil Skies]], and [[Blueface]]. The music video, has surpassed thirty million views as of April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8548634/jack-harlow-whats-poppin-video|title=Jack Harlow Bounces Around the Diner in Cole Bennett-Directed 'Whats Poppin' Video: Watch|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/jack-harlow-snaps-on-braggadocios-banger-whats-poppin-new-song.1985876.html|title=Jack Harlow Snaps On Braggadocios Banger \"What's Poppin'\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Jack Harlow - WHATS POPPIN (Dir. by @_ColeBennett_)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w9uWPBDHEKE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> On his most recent birthday, March 13, 2020, he released a seven-track project called ''Sweet Action''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jack-harlow-ep-sweet-action|title=Listen to Jack Harlow's EP 'Sweet Action'|work=Complex|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Mixtapes===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of mixtapes with selected album details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Finally Handsome''\n|\n* Released: November 7, 2014\n* Label: [[Independent music|Self-released]]\n* Formats: [[Music download|Digital download]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''18''\n|\n* Released: June 17, 2016\n* Label: Self-released\n* Formats: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Gazebo''\n|\n* Released: November 17, 2017\n* Label: Self-released\n* Formats: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Loose''\n|\n* Released: August 17, 2018\n* Label: Generation Now, [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* Formats: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Confetti''\n|\n* Released: S